{"title_page": "Suceava", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|\nofficial_name=Suceava\n| settlement_type = City\n|image_skyline={{nowrap|[[File:Palatul Administrativ din Suceava12.jpg|260px]]<br />[[File:Cl\u0103direa Palatului de Justi\u021bie din Suceava1.jpg|130px]][[File:Muzeul Judetean din Suceava11.jpg|130px]]<br />[[File:Gara Burdujeni1.jpg|130px]][[File:Cetatea de Scaun a Sucevei17.jpg|130px]]<br />[[File:M\u0103n\u0103stirea Sf\u00e2ntul Ioan cel Nou26.jpg|x92px]][[File:Biserica Sf. Apostoli din Itcani8.jpg|x92px]][[File:Biserica Sf\u00e2ntul Ioan Nepomuk din Suceava.jpg|x92px]]}}\n|image_caption = Left to right: the Administrative Palace, Palace of Justice, Bukovina History Museum, Burdujeni Train Station, The Medieval Seat Fortress, St. John the New Monastery, St. Apostles Church in I\u0163cani, St. John of Nepomuk Church\n| image_shield = ROU SV Suceava CoA.png\n|map_caption            = Location in Suceava County\n|image_map              = Suceava jud Suceava.png\n| pushpin_map             = Romania#Europe\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location of Suceava\n|coordinates  = {{coord|47|39|05|N|26|15|20|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{ROU}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Counties of Romania|County]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Subdivisions of Romania|Status]]\n|\nsubdivision_name1=[[Suceava County]]\n|\nsubdivision_name2={{Autolink|County capital}}\n|leader_party=[[National Liberal Party (Romania)|PNL]]\n|leader_title = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name=Ion Lungu<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|\n| area_total_km2            = 52.10\n| area_land_km2             =\n| area_water_km2            =\n| area_metro_km2            = 473.29\n|population_as_of  = {{Romania metadata Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n|population_total  = {{Romania metadata Wikidata|population_total}} \n|population_footnotes = {{Romania metadata Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n|population_density_km2=auto\n| pop_est_as_of             = 2018\n| population_est            = 124,161 {{increase}}\n| pop_est_footnotes         = <ref name=\"INSSE 2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-esential-23123474-harta-interactiva-cati-mai-suntem-romania-populatia-fiecare-judet-fiecare-municipiu-din-tara.htm| title= HART\u0102 INTERACTIV\u0102 - C\u00e2\u021bi mai suntem \u00een Rom\u00e2nia? Popula\u021bia \u00een fiecare jude\u021b \u0219i \u00een fiecare municipiu din \u021bar\u0103|date=6 May 2019|accessdate = 6 May 2019|publisher = [[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|INSSE]]|language=Romanian}}</ref>\n| population_metro          = 176,016<ref name=\"luz\">{{cite web|url= http://www.insse.ro/cms/sites/default/files/field/publicatii/populatia_romaniei_pe_localitati_la_1ianuarie2016_0.pdf#page120| title=Population on 1 January by age groups and sex - functional urban areas | accessdate=29 October 2017 | publisher=[[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|INSSE]]|language=Romanian}}</ref>\n| population_note           =\n|\nwebsite=http://www.primariasv.ro/\n|timezone=[[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset=+2\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n|\n|\n|\n||\n||\nblank_name=[[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n|\nblank_info=[[Humid continental climate#Mild/cool summer subtype|Dfb]]\n|\n}}\n\n'''Suceava''' ({{IPA-ro|su\u02c8t\u0283e\u032fava|lang}}, {{lang-de|Suczawa}}) is the largest city and the seat of [[Suceava County]], situated in the historical region of [[Moldavia]], north-eastern [[Romania]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/place/Suceava-county-Romania| title=County of Suceava| work=Encyclopaedia Britannica|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref> and at the crossroads of [[Central Europe|Central]] and [[Eastern Europe]] respectively.<ref name=\"books.google.co.uk\">Klaus Peter Berger, [https://books.google.com/books?id=gEeP9NY2qGkC&pg=PA132&dq=Bukovina+part+of++%22Central+Europe%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=aDHHT7-aCYee8gOV4Iz5DQ&ved=0CDkQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=partof%20Central%20Europe&f=false The Creeping Codification of the New Lex Mercatoria], Kluwer Law International, 2010, p. 132</ref> During the late [[Middle Ages]], more specifically from 1388 to 1564, the city was the third capital of the [[Moldavia|Principality of Moldavia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rri.ro/de_de/suceava_die_geschichtsbeladene_stadt_in_der_bukowina-2542507|author=Daniel Onea, Adina Olaru|work=Radio Rom\u00e2nia Interna\u021bional|title=Suceava \u2013 die geschichtsbeladene Stadt in der Bukowina (in German)|date=27 January 2016|accessdate= 1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theculturetrip.com/europe/romania/articles/the-10-most-beautiful-towns-in-romania|author=Lani Seelinger|work=The Culture Trip|title=The 10 Most Beautiful Towns In Romania|accessdate= 28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1775 and 1918, Suceava was controlled by the [[Habsburg Monarchy]], first as part of its [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]], then became the third most populous urban settlement of the [[Duchy of Bukovina]] ({{lang-de|Herzogtum Bukowina}}),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philhist.uni-augsburg.de/lehrstuehle/volkskunde/Exkursionen/Ukraine/Cz_Bukowina-Deutsche|author=Alexander Weidle|work=University of Augsburg|title=Bukowina Deutsche (in German)|date=10 December 2017|accessdate= 1 October 2018}}</ref> a constituent province of the [[Austrian Empire]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phdthesis.uaic.ro/PhDThesis/%C8%9Aurca%C8%99,%20Ioan,%20Lucian,%20Macarie,%20German%20Language%20and%20Culture%20in%20Southern%20Bukovina-%20The%20Disappearance%20of%20a%20Cultural%20Enclave.pdf|author=\u021aurca\u0219, Ioan, Lucian, Macarie|work=Abstract of PhD thesis|title=German Language and Culture in Southern Bukovina. The Disappearance of a Cultural Enclave|accessdate= 1 October 2018}}</ref> and subsequently a crown land within [[Austria-Hungary]]. It was only surpassed by [[Chernivtsi|Cern\u0103u\u021bi]] ({{lang-de|Czernowitz}}) and [[R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]] ({{lang-de|Radautz}}), both located to the north. Furthermore, thanks to its diverse ethnic background during the Modern Age, Austrian architect Rudolf Gassauer stated that the city of Suceava could have well been perceived as a 'miniature Austria'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dragusanul.ro/marturia-lui-rudolf-gassauer/|author=Dragu\u0219anul.ro|work=Dr\u0103gu\u0219anul|title=M\u0103rturia lui Rudolf Gassauer (in Romanian)|accessdate= 8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, Suceava was an important, strategically-located commercial border town with the then [[Romanian Old Kingdom]] ({{lang-de|Altreich}}). It received a large influx of [[German language|German]]-speaking settlers in the process of the [[Josephine colonization]] ({{lang-de|Josephinische Siedlung}}). This community has since dwindled to a very small number.<ref>{{cite web|title=Portr\u00e4t der Deutschen Minderheit - Geschichte zum Nachh\u00f6ren (in German) |work=Pausen Radio |author= www.pausenradio.net |url= http://pausenradio.net/wpress/?p=1429 |date=25 October 2015 |accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Geschichte einer Minderheit noch nicht zu Ende geschrieben (in German) |work= Allgemeine Deutsche Zeitung f\u00fcr Rum\u00e4nien, www.adz.ro |url= http://www.adz.ro/artikel/artikel/geschichte-einer-minderheit-noch-nicht-zu-ende-geschrieben |author=Robert Tari |date=20 September 2015 |accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of [[World War I]], after 1918, [[Union of Bukovina with the Kingdom of Romania|along with the rest of Bukovina]], Suceava became part of the then newly enlarged [[Kingdom of Romania]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://europecentenary.eu/declaration-of-union-of-bukovina-with-the-kingdom-of-romania| title=Declaration of Union of Bukovina with the Kingdom of Romania (in English)|work=Europe Centenary|date=13 August 2018| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> After the end of [[World War II]], the city slowly underwent a process of forced Communist urbanization which increased its population about tenfold throughout the decades before the [[Romanian Revolution|1989 revolution]]. It became a municipality ({{lang-ro|municipiu}}) in 1968.\n\n=={{anchor|Names and etymology}}Names and etymology==\n{{see also|Names of Suceava in different languages}}\n\nMoldavian chronicler [[Grigore Ureche]] presumed the name of the city came from the [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] ''Sz\u0171csv\u00e1r'', which is combined of the words ''sz\u0171cs'' (furrier, skinner) and ''v\u00e1r'' (castle). This was taken over by [[Dimitrie Cantemir]], who in his work ''[[:s:la:Descriptio Moldaviae|Descriptio Moldaviae]]'' gave the very same explanation of the origin of the city's name, however, there are neither historical nor vernacular evidences for this. According to another theory, the city bears the name of the [[Suceava (river)|river]] with the same name, that is supposed to be of [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] origin.<ref name=debrecen>{{cite book |last=Hoffmann |first=Istv\u00e1n |title=Helyn\u00e9vt\u00f6rt\u00e9neti tanulm\u00e1nyok 3. |year=2008 |publisher=University of Debrecen, Department of Hungarian Linguistics |location=Debrecen |isbn=978-963-473-115-3|page=212}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Old High German|Old German]] ({{lang-de|Altdeutsch}}) the city was known as ''Sedschopff'',<ref>[[Johann Schiltberger]]. ''[https://archive.org/details/hansschiltberge00langgoog Hans Schiltbergers Reisebuch]'' T\u00fcbingen, Litterarischer Verein in Stuttgart, 1885, p. 111</ref> in [[German language|High German]] sources it can be found under such variations as ''Sotschen'',<ref>Peter Kosta (Hrsg.): Eine russische Kosmographie aus dem 17. Jahrhundert: sprachwissenschaftliche Analyse mit Textedition und Faksimile, Otto Sagner, 1982. {{ISBN|3-87690-200-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.burgenwelt.org/rumaenien/lokal/lokal2-suceava.php#links|work = Burgenwelt| author = Andy Winkler| date = 13 February 2015| title = Jude\u021bul Suceava, Kreis Suceava, Burgen und andere Wehrbauten (in German)| accessdate = 6 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.burgenwelt.org/rumaenien/suceava/object.php#historie|work = Burgenwelt| author = Andy Winkler| date = 13 February 2015| title = Cetatea de Scaun, Festung Suceava (in German)| accessdate = 6 March 2020}}</ref>''Sutschawa'', or ''Suczawa'', in Hungarian as ''Szucs\u00e1va''<ref name=debrecen /> ({{IPA-hu|\u02c8sut\u0361\u0283a\u02d0v\u0252|}}) or ''Sz\u0151csv\u00e1s\u00e1r'', in [[Polish language|Polish]] as  ''Suczawa'', in Ukrainian as ''\u0421\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0432\u0430'' (Su\u010dava), while in [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]] as \u05e9\u05d0\u05b8\u05e5 ({{IPA-yi|\u0283\u0254ts|}}).<ref>For Yiddish spelling and pronunciation, see [http://shotzer.com/zope/home/en/1/homepage_en/ \"Shotzer - the book of the Jews of Suceava\"] {{ISBN|965-7226-16-3}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Franz Xavier Knapp - Gr\u00e4nz-Stadt Suczarva.jpg|thumb|left|Artist's impression of the city Suceava from 1867 by Austrian painter [[:de:Franz Xaver Knapp|Franz Xaver Knapp.]]]]\n[[File:1 \u0421\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0432\u0430.jpg|thumb|left|Artist's impression of the city of Suceava from 1870 by Austrian painter [[:de:Franz Xaver Knapp|Franz Xaver Knapp.]]]]\n[[File:Ceausescu la Suceava 1970.jpg|thumb|right|Former Communist dictator [[Nicolae Ceau\u0219escu]] visting Suceava in 1970.]]\n\nThe present-day territory of the city of Suceava and the adjacent surroundings were already inhabited since the [[Paleolithic]] period. Stemming from the late [[Ancient history|Antiquity]], there are also traces of [[Dacian tribe|Dacian]] [[oppidum]] of the 2nd century.\n\nIn stark contrast to several [[historical regions of Romania]] (most notably [[Transylvania]] and [[Oltenia]]), Suceava (along with the entire region of Bukovina for that matter) was not conquered by the legions of the [[Roman Empire]] and consequently was one of the lands of the [[Free Dacians|Free Dacian tribes]] during the late Ancient Age. Nonetheless, according to [[Ptolemy]], at that time in the region also dwelled two likely [[Celts|Celtic]]-speaking tribes, specifically the [[Anartes]] and the [[Taurisci]],<ref>Ptolemy III.8.5</ref> as well as the [[Germanic peoples|Germanic]] [[Bastarnae]], who have also been attested there.<ref name=\"Barrington Map 22\">Barrington Map 22</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Fall of the Western Roman Empire|fall of Rome]] and during the [[Migration Period]], the predominantly [[Carpi (people)|Carpiani]] population was successively invaded by [[East Germanic tribes|East Germanic peoples]] (such as the [[Goths]] or the [[Gepids]]), [[Huns]], [[Slavs]], [[Hungarians|Magyars]], [[Pechenegs]], and ultimately [[Cumans]]. During the [[Late Middle Ages]], the city of Suceava was the capital of the [[Principality of Moldavia]] and the main residence of the Moldavian [[List of rulers of Moldavia|princes]] for nearly two centuries (namely between 1388 and 1564).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/place/Suceava-Romania| title=Encyclopaedia Britannica - City of Suceava}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://muzeulbucovinei.ro/en/arhive/11738| title= Muzeul Bucovinei - Princely Fortress of Suceava (in Romanian)| author=Muzeul Bucovinei}}</ref>\n\nThe city was the capital of the lands of [[Stephen III of Moldavia|Stephen the Great]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bukowinafreunde.de/geschichte.html |title= Die Bukowina |author=Bukowina Freunde |work= www.bukowinafreunde.de |language= German |accessdate= 1 October 2018}}</ref> one of the pivotal figures in Romanian history, who died in Suceava in 1504. During the rule of [[Alexandru L\u0103pu\u0219neanu]], the seat was moved to [[Ia\u0219i]] in 1565 and Suceava failed to become the capital again. [[Michael the Brave]] captured the city in 1600 during the [[Moldavian Magnate Wars]] as he became the ruler of [[Wallachia]], [[Moldavia]], and [[Transylvania]], but he was defeated the same year.\n\n[[File:Platforma_industriala_Valea_Sucevei.jpg|thumb|right|Suceava valley industrial platform, bird's-eye view taken at some point during the 1960s.]]\n\nTogether with the rest of [[Bukovina]] ({{lang-de|Buchenland}}), Suceava was under the rule of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] (and, later, the [[Austrian Empire]] as well as [[Austria-Hungary]]) from 1775 to 1918 (with the border of the Habsburg domains passing just south-east of the city).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goethe.de/resources/files/pdf134/minoritatea-germana-din-romania1.pdf| work= Goethe Institut| title=Minoritatea german\u0103 din Rom\u00e2nia de Winfried Ziegler (in Romanian)| accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref> During the late 19th century and early 20th century, the city was the third largest in the [[Duchy of Bukovina]], after [[Chernivtsi|Cern\u0103u\u021bi]] and [[R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]].\n\nIn 1918, the city of Suceava (as well as the entire region of Bukovina) became part of what is known as '[[Greater Romania]]', after an overwhelming vote of the German, Romanian, and Polish representatives of the [[General Congress of Bukovina]]. Throughout the interwar period, Suceava undergone further infrastructural development within the then enlarged [[Kingdom of Romania]]. Moreover, from an administrative point of view, it had also briefly belonged to [[\u021ainutul Suceava]] (between 1938 and 1940), one of the 10 lands established during [[Carol II of Romania|King Carol II of Romania]]'s reign.\n\nSubsequently, from the 1950s onwards (along with the onset of [[Socialist Republic of Romania|Communism]]), Suceava was heavily industrialized and a significant series of historical buildings from its old city centre were demolished in order for [[Plattenbau]]-like blocks of flats to be constructed at the orders of the [[Romanian Communist Party|Communist officials]].<ref>The Rough Guide to Romania, {{ISBN|978-1-84353-326-9}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n\n[[File:Around Suceava, Romania (10766493523).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Arable land near the city of Suceava, as seen from above.]]\n\nThe city covers two types of geographical areas, the hills (of which the highest is Zamca Hill) and the meadows of the [[Suceava (river)|Suceava]] river valley.<ref>[https://civitas.eu/cs/content/suceava Suceava's profile on www.civitas.eu]</ref> The unique setting of the urban settlement includes two groves, Zamca and \u0218ipote, which are both located within the city limits. Burdujeni, one of the neighbourhoods, is connected to the rest of the city by a prominent avenue, which makes the neighbourhood appear to be a separate [[satellite town]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Austrian and Romanian census data and/or official estimates\n| 1910 | 10,955\n| 1912 | 11,229\n| 1930 | 17,028\n| 1948 | 10,123\n| 1956 | 20,949\n| 1966 | 37,697\n| 1977 | 62,715\n| 1992 | 114,462\n| 2002 | 106,138\n| 2011 | 92,121\n| 2016 | 116,404\n| 2018 | 124,161\n}}\n\nIn 1910, when the city was still under Imperial Austrian administration, the total population amounted to 10,955 inhabitants. Of those, 61.5% declared their native language to be [[German language|German]] (i.e. ''Hochdeutsch''), followed by [[Romanian language|Romanian]] with 25.38% and [[Ruthenian language|Ruthenian]] (or [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]) with 5.46%. 20 years later, when the city switched to royal Romanian administration, the [[Demographic history of Romania#29 December 1930 census|1930 census]] recorded a population which amounted to {{circa}} 17,000 inhabitants with the following ethno-linguistic composition:<ref>{{cite web| url=https://archive.org/stream/recensamntulgene02inst#page/434/mode/2up| title=Recens\u0103m\u00e2nul general al popula\u021biei Rom\u00e2niei din 29 decemvrie 1930}}</ref>\n\n* [[Romanians]]: 60.2%\n* [[Germans of Romania|Germans]] <small>(i.e. [[Bukovina Germans]])</small>: 16.7%\n* [[History of the Jews in Romania|Jews]]: 15.4%\n* [[Ukrainians of Romania|Ukrainians]]: 3.7%\n* [[Poles in Romania|Poles]]: 2.0%\n\nAccording to the [[Demographic history of Romania#20 October 2011 census|2011 census]] data, Suceava had a population of 92,121,<ref name=\"INSSER\">{{cite web | url = http://www.suceava.insse.ro/phpfiles/Comunicat%20-%20pt%20site-DATE%20PROVIZORII%20RPL%202011%202_Suceava.pdf | title = 2011 Census | date = February 2, 2012 | access-date = March 12, 2012 | publisher = [[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|INSSE]] | language = Romanian | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130604040638/http://www.suceava.insse.ro/phpfiles/Comunicat%20-%20pt%20site-DATE%20PROVIZORII%20RPL%202011%202_Suceava.pdf | archive-date = June 4, 2013 | df =  }}</ref> a decrease from the figure recorded at the 2002 census (106,138), making it the 23rd [[List of cities and towns in Romania|largest city]] in Romania at that time. Additionally, the ethnic composition was as follows:\n\n* [[Romanians]]: 98.3%\n* [[Romani people|Roma]]: 0.7%\n* [[Ukrainians in Romania|Ukrainians]]: 0.3%\n* [[Germans of Romania|Germans]] <small>(i.e. [[Bukovina Germans]])</small>: 0.2%\n* [[Poles in Romania|Poles]]: 0.1%\n* [[Lipovans]]: 0.1%\n* Other ethnic groups: 0.3%\n\n== Administration and local politics ==\n\n=== List of mayors (1990\u2013present) ===\n\n[[File:Franz Des Loges.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Former [[Austria]]n-born mayor [[:ro:Franz Des Loges|Franz Des Loges]] (of [[Swiss people|Swiss-French]] origin) is credited with modernising the city as well as developing its culture and infrastructure during his term (1891\u20131914).<ref>{{cite web|title=Primarul austriac care a adus energia electric\u0103, iluminatul public, alimentarea cu ap\u0103, canalizarea \u015fi str\u0103zile asfaltate \u00een Suceava|work=Ziarul Adev\u0103rul|author=www.adevarul.ro|url=https://adevarul.ro/locale/suceava/primarul-austriac-adus-energia-electricailuminatul-public-alimentarea-apa-canalizarea-strazile-asfaltate-insuceava-1_54c9de4b448e03c0fd103ef9/index.html|date=29 January 2015|accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>]]\n\nThe mayors who have administered the city since Romania's transition back to [[democracy]] and a free [[market economy]] in the wake of the [[Romanian Revolution|1989 revolution]] have been the following ones:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=1 | N\u00ba\n! colspan=1 | Name\n! colspan=1 | Term start\n! colspan=1 | Term end\n! colspan=1 | Political party\n|-bgcolor={{Independent/meta/color}}\n! 1\n| Filaret Poenariu\n| 1990\n| 1992\n| [[Independent politician|Independent]]\n|-bgcolor={{Ecologist Party of Romania/meta/color}}\n! 2\n| Gheorghe Toma\n| 1992\n| 1996\n| [[Ecologist Party of Romania]] (PER)\n|-bgcolor={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}\n! 3\n| [[:ro:Constantin Sofroni|Constantin Sofroni]]\n| 1996\n| 2000\n| [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party]] (PNL)<sup>1</sup>\n|-bgcolor={{Social Democratic Party (Romania)/meta/color}}\n! 4\n| Marian Ionescu\n| 2000\n| 2004\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party]] (PSD)\n|-bgcolor={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}\n! 5\n| [[:ro:Ion Lungu|Ion Lungu]]\n| 2004\n| present\n| [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party]] (PNL)<sup>2</sup>\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Notes''':\n\n<sup>1</sup> <small>Initially elected on the lists of the [[Democratic Agrarian Party of Romania]] (PDAR) but subsequently switched to the National Liberal Party (PNL).</small><ref>{{cite web|title=Fostul primar Constantin Sofroni, cet\u0103\u021bean de onoare post-mortem|work=Crai Nou|author=www.crainou.ro|url=https://www.crainou.ro/2005/03/18/fostul-primar-constantin-sofroni-cetatean-de-onoare-post-mortem/|date=18 March 2005|accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n<br>\n<sup>2</sup> <small>Initially elected on the lists of the [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party]] (PNL), subsequently switched to the [[Democratic Liberal Party (Romania)|Democratic Liberal Party]], then re-elected on the lists of the PNL</small>\n\n=== City council ===\n\n[[File:Primaria municipiului Suceava2.jpg|thumb|right|Suceava City Hall]]\n\nThe city's current local council has the following multi-party political composition, based on the results of the ballots cast at the [[2016 Romanian local elections]]:\n\n{| cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Party\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Seats\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" colspan=\"10\" | Current Council\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party (PNL)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''10'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party (PSD)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''8'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (Romania)|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (ALDE)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''3'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| [[People's Movement Party|People's Movement Party (PMP)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|}\n\n==Culture==\n\n===The Seat Fortress of Suceava===\n\n[[File:Cetatea de Scaun a Sucevei13.jpg|thumb|right|The access bridge and circular bastion of the seat fortress.]]\n\nSuceava is the place of several medieval sites that are closely linked with the history of the former [[Moldavia|Principality of Moldavia]]. By far the most significant (and at the same time the most well preserved one) is the Seat Fortress of Suceava ({{lang-ro|Cetatea de Scaun a Sucevei}}) or Suceava Citadel, a medieval castle situated on the eastern edge of the contemporary city.\n\nThe fortress was built during the reign of [[Petru II of Moldavia|Petru of Moldavia]] (1375\u20131391), also known as Petru Mu\u0219at. It was further expanded and strengthened during the reigns of [[Alexander I of Moldavia]] (1400\u20131432) and [[Stephen III of Moldavia|Stephen the Great]] (1457\u20131504). The medieval castle was part of the fortification system built in [[Moldavia]] in the late 14th century, because of the emergence of the Ottoman danger. It became strong enough to hold off an attack by Ottoman sultan [[Mehmed II]] (the conqueror of [[Constantinople]]), in 1476.\n\nSuceava was the capital city of the former Principality of Moldavia between 1388 and 1565. During this period, the castle served as princely residence. [[Alexandru L\u0103pu\u0219neanu]] had subsequently moved the Moldavian capital to [[Ia\u0219i]] in 1565, so the castle lost its status. Afterwards, the citadel entered a period of steep decline. In 1675, during the reign of voivode Dumitra\u0219cu Cantacuzino, the fortress was destroyed. Then, for over two centuries, the castle was completely deserted.\n\n[[File:Cetatea de Scaun a Sucevei la ceas de seara.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The late 14th century Moldavian seat fortress as seen during nighttime in May, 2015.]]\n\nIn late 19th century and early 20th century, under the patronage of Austrian architect [[:ro:Karl Romstorfer|Karl Adolf Romstorfer]], a series of rehabilitation works and archaeological research were conducted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dragusanul.ro/romstorfer-vienezul-care-a-indatorat-bucovina/|author=Dragu\u0219anul.ro|work=Dr\u0103gu\u0219anul|title=Romstorfer, vienezul care a \u00eendatorat Bucovina (in Romanian)|accessdate= 8 March 2020}}</ref> Between 1961 and 1970 other restoration and consolidation works were carried out. In 2013, a major reconstruction program was launched, to return the castle to its original architecture and shape.\n\nThe Seat Fortress of Suceava consists of two concentric citadels. The inner citadel, known as ''fortul mu\u0219atin'', has a rectangular shape and a patio. It was built by Petru Mu\u0219at in late 14th century. In the second half of the 15th century, Stephen the Great expanded the structure, by adding another citadel that has a circular shape which surrounds the old one.\n\nAfter 1476, new fortifications were added to the outer citadel. Furthermore, the whole castle is encircled by a large defensive ditch. Today, the fortress is a landmark of Suceava and a noteworthy touristic attraction. Since 2011, it has also been used for hosting cultural events such as the [[rock music]] festival Bucovina Rock Castle. The festival had attracted a series of noteworthy national and international musical acts (e.g. guitarist [[Jan Akkerman]], formerly of Dutch [[progressive rock]] band [[Focus (band)|Focus]]).<ref>[http://www.bucovinarockcastle.ro Bucovina Rock Castle official website (in Romanian)]</ref>\n\n===The Princely Court of Suceava===\n\n[[File:Curtea domneasca din Suceava9.jpg|thumb|left|Present-day ruins of the local Princely Court.]]\n\nThe Princely Court of Suceava ({{lang-ro|Curtea Domneasc\u0103 din Suceava}}) was built and developed related with the Seat Fortress. In late 14th century, voivode Petru Mu\u0219at built the Princely House, a structure made in wood, which included a cellar. After 1400, Alexander I of Moldavia rebuilt the wooden house and added a surrounding wall made of stone and a complex of buildings, also made of stone. In the second half of the 15th century, the Princely Court was severely affected by fire, the wooden house being completely burned out.\n\nDuring his reign, Stephen the Great (1457\u20131504) restored the whole complex. A new Princely House was built, this time made of stone, and the other buildings were extended. [[Vasile Lupu]] (1634\u20131653) was the last ruler of Moldavia who took care of the Princely Court. During his time, the cellars were rehabilitated. The complex was abandoned in late 17th century, the buildings and the walls being gradually dismantled. Currently, on the site of the Princely Court there are only ruins and leftovers of the former buildings.\n\nThe ruins of the former medieval court are located in the city center of Suceava. In the 14th\u201317th centuries, in the proximity of the Princely Court there were built several churches that still exist today and attract tourists.\n\n[[File:Cetatea \u015echeia10.jpg|thumb|right|The ruined walls of the \u0218cheia Fortress on \u0218eptilici Hill.]]\n\n===\u0218cheia Fortress===\n\nOn the north-western edge of the contemporary city, on a hilltop, there is another medieval citadel known as ''\u0218cheia'' Fortress ({{lang-ro|Cetatea \u0218cheia}}) or the Western Fortress of Suceava ({{lang-ro|Cetatea de Apus a Sucevei}}). Unlike the Seat Fortress, ''\u0218cheia'' Fortress has left nothing but some ruined walls. The citadel proper was built during the reign of Petru Mu\u0219at during the late 14th century, but was short-lived, given that it was dismantled during the early 15th century, in the time of [[Alexander I of Moldavia]]. ''\u0218cheia'' Fortress, just like the main Seat Fortress, was part of the fortification system built in medieval Principality of Moldavia during the late 14th century.\n\n===Museums===\n\n[[File:Muzeul Judetean din Suceava7.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The entrance to the Bukovina History Museum. During the [[interwar period]], the building served as Suceava County prefecture.]]\n\nThe first museum in Suceava was opened in 1900, by the initiative of some local intellectuals. In the beginning, the museum included only a few collections that were obtained as a result of the researches and excavation works at the Seat Fortress of Suceava. The museum was expanded and developed over time and became an important cultural institution, currently named [[Bukovina Museum]] ({{lang-ro|Muzeul Bucovinei}}). It has several departments and administers the medieval sites of the Seat Fortress, ''\u0218cheia'' Fortress and the Princely Court, local museums (Bukovina Village Museum, the history, ethnographic, and natural sciences museums), the memorial houses of [[Simion Florea Marian]] in Suceava, [[Nicolae Labi\u0219]] in [[M\u0103lini]], [[:ro:Eusebiu Camilar|Eusebiu Camilar]] in [[Ude\u0219ti]], [[Ciprian Porumbescu]] in [[Ciprian Porumbescu, Suceava|Stupca]], and two traditional houses located in [[Solca]] and [[Bilca]].\n\nThe oldest department of Bukovina Museum is the history museum, which was the backbone for creating a county museum at Suceava. This museum presents the local history of Suceava and Moldavia in the context of Romanian national history. The exhibits of the history museum and the offices of Bukovina Museum are located in a historic building, in the city center. The building, which hosted the prefecture of Suceava County during the interwar period, was built between 1902\u20131903. Since 1968, it houses the history museum. In 2014, the building and the museum entered an extensive program of modernization, rehabilitation, and expansion.\n\n{{multiple image|perrow=2|total_width=300|align=left\n|image1 = Cr\u00e2\u0219ma din \u0218aru Dornei - panoramio.jpg|caption1=Inn from [[Vatra Dornei|Dorna]] ({{lang-de|Dorna Watra}}) ethnographic area, exhibited at Bukovina Village Museum\n|image2 = Casa Vicovu de Jos1.jpg|caption2=Traditional household from [[Vicovu de Jos]] ({{lang-de|Unter Wikow}})\n|image3 = Gospod\u0103ria Straja6.jpg|caption3=Traditional household from [[Straja, Suceava|Straja]] ({{lang-de|Strasza}})\n|image4 = Moara din M\u0103n\u0103stirea Humorului.jpg|caption4=Windmill from [[M\u0103n\u0103stirea Humorului]] ({{lang-de|Humora Kloster}})\n}}\n\nAt the history museum there is a reconstitution of a scene from the former throne hall located in the Seat Fortress. The scene presents some notable people from the history of Moldavia, made in glass fiber: [[Stephen III of Moldavia|Stephen the Great]] (ruler of Moldavia), Maria Voichi\u021ba (his third wife), [[Bogdan III the One-Eyed]] (his son and successor to the throne), officials of that time. The scene chosen to be reconstructed is an allotment of land for peasants. The reconstitution is based on medieval documents, frescoes and archaeological researches. Furthermore, the history museum periodically organizes a wide range of cultural events, several of which also involve the local branch of the [[Democratic Forum of Germans in Romania]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.istorielocala.ro/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=878:forumul-democrat-al-germanilor-din-bucovina&Itemid=204|author=www.istorielocala.ro|work=Istoria Local\u0103 @ biblioteca ta public\u0103|title=Forumul Democrat al Germanilor din Bucovina (in Romanian)|date= 14 October 2013| accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adz.ro/artikel/artikel/die-geschichte-der-deutschen-in-rumaenien-wurde-noch-nicht-zu-ende-geschrieben/|author=www.adz.ro|work=Allgemeine Deutsche Zeitung f\u00fcr Rum\u00e4nien|title=Die Geschichte der Deutschen in Rum\u00e4nien wurde noch nicht zu Ende geschrieben (in German)|date= 8 January 2014| accessdate= 1 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nBukovina Village Museum ({{lang-ro|Muzeul Satului Bucovinean}}) is an open-air museum that highlights the traditional cultural and architectural heritage of [[Bukovina]] region. It is located in the eastern part of Suceava, near the Seat Fortress. It was founded in the 1970s, but its major expansion and development took place after 1990. The museum is designed as a traditional village in Bukovina, containing houses and various objectives from the ethnographic areas of [[R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]], [[Gura Humorului|Humor]], [[C\u00e2mpulung Moldovenesc]], [[Vatra Dornei|Dorna]], and [[F\u0103lticeni]].\n\nThe museum includes among others a water mill from [[M\u0103n\u0103stirea Humorului]], a traditional blacksmith workshop, a pottery workshop from [[Marginea]] and one of the many old wooden churches in northern Moldavia: Church of the Ascension, a Romanian Orthodox wooden church built in 1783 in [[Vama, Suceava|Vama]], a village in [[Suceava County]]. The bell tower is also made in wood, and dates from 1787. The church and the bell tower were both relocated in 2001, and currently are part of the museum.\n\n[[File:Hanul Domnesc din Suceava9.jpg|thumb|right|Entrance to the Princely Inn (now Ethnographic Museum)]]\n\nBesides Bukovina Village Museum, another museum that reflects the traditional life in this part of Romania is the ethnographic museum. It was opened in 1968 and includes old collections and exhibits that are housed in a medieval inn located in the center of Suceava, known as the Princely Inn of Suceava ({{lang-ro|Hanul Domnesc din Suceava}}). This landmark dates from the late 16th and early 17th century. It was built of stone and has two floors and a cellar. During the Austrian rule (1775\u20131918), the inn operated as a hunting lodge for the imperial family. Since 1968, it hosts the ethnographic museum. The Princely Inn is the oldest civic building in Suceava which had not been seriously affected by time and maintained its original architecture.\n\n[[File:Muzeul de Stiintele Naturii din Suceava4.jpg|thumb|right|Natural Sciences Museum]]\n\nThe natural sciences museum was founded in 1976\u20131977, being the newest museum in Suceava. It highlights the flora and fauna of the surrounding area. The museum's rare exhibits and collections are housed in an old building, located in the central park of the city and built between 1811\u20131814. In the past, before being an attraction for visitors, the building operated as a school for boys.\n\nAlong with all these museums, Bukovina Museum includes memorial houses of some writers and artists born in this area of the country. The memorial house of Simion Florea Marian ({{lang-ro|Casa memorial\u0103 Simion Florea Marian}}) is the only one located in Suceava, the other ones being in the surrounding area. The memorial house operates as a museum. It was opened in 1974 in the home where Romanian priest and writer Simion Florea Marian lived, from 1884 until 1907, when he died. The museum hosts a collection that contains over 10,000 volumes, over 450 collections of magazines and newspapers, of which 150 are from [[Bukovina]], manuscripts, letters, cultural and historical documents, old photos. In front of the memorial house it was opened a small park with a statue dedicated to Simion Florea Marian.\n\n===Historical buildings===\n\n[[File:Casa Aleea Trandafirilor nr. 4 din Suceava1.jpg|thumb|left|Austrian-style house situated in the old city centre.]]\n\n''Colegiul de Art\u0103 Ciprian Porumbescu'' ({{lang-ro|Ciprian Porumbescu Art College}}) is a high school which is hosted in a historic building, built in 1859, in the city center of Suceava. The building had several destinations in the past: Suceava Town Hall (until 1904) and ''\u0218coala primar\u0103 rom\u00e2n\u0103 de fete'' (Primary Romanian school for girls). Romanian jazz singer [[Anca Parghel]] taught music for a living in Suceava at this local Arts high school before turning to a professional singing career in 1989.\n\n[[File:Gara Suceava Nord.jpg|right|thumb|I\u021bcani ({{lang-de|Itzkany}}) railway station during the early 20th century.]]\n[[File:Suceava railway station (39856700481).jpg|thumb|right|Burdujeni railway station during the early 20th century.]]\n\n''Gara Suceava Nord-I\u021bcani'' ([[Suceava North railway station]], also known as ''I\u021bcani'') is a train station built in 1871 in the village of [[I\u021bcani]] (today district of Suceava). Between 1871\u20131918, it was a train station at the Austro-Hungarian border. The historic building of I\u021bcani railway station was built in the Gothic style of the Central European railway stations of that period.\n\n''Palatul de Justi\u021bie'' (The Palace of Justice) is a historic building which was built in 1885 to serve as the seat of Suceava Tribunal and Court. The building has four sides and a patio, and was designed by Viennese architect [[Fellner & Helmer|Ferdinand Fellner]]. Later, during the communist regime, the city hall was moved in this palace and operated here until 2000.\n\n''Spitalul Vechi'' (The Old Hospital) is a complex of buildings built between 1891\u20131903 which originally hosted the district hospital. The hospital ensemble consists of four pavilions of historic value and was built in the southwestern end of Suceava, in Areni neighborhood. In 1964 a new hospital building (known as ''Spitalul Nou'') was inaugurated nearby.\n\n''Colegiul Na\u021bional \u0218tefan cel Mare'' (\u0218tefan cel Mare National College) is the oldest and most prestigious high school in [[Suceava County]], established in 1860. The baroque style building which houses the high school was built between 1893\u20131895, downtown Suceava, and today is considered a historical monument.\n\n[[File:Palatul Administrativ din Suceava19.jpg|thumb|left|The Administrative Palace during the interwar period]]\n[[File:BRC Sv.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.9|St. John of Nepomuk Roman Catholic church in 1990]]\n\n''Gara Suceava-Burdujeni'' ([[Suceava railway station]], also known as ''Burdujeni'') is a train station built between 1892\u20131902 in the village of Burdujeni (today district of Suceava). Between 1902\u20131918, it was a train station at the Austro-Hungarian border. The historic building of Burdujeni railway station was built in the architectural style of [[Fribourg]] railway station, located in [[Switzerland]].\n\n[[File:Biblioteca Bucovinei I.G. Sbiera din Suceava1.jpg|thumb|right|I.G. Sbiera Bukovina Library]]\n[[File:Directia Silvica Judeteana din Suceava1.jpg|thumb|right|The County Forestry Department in Suceava]]\n[[File:Primaria din Burdujeni.jpg|thumb|right|Former Burdujeni town hall building]]\n\n''Palatul Administrativ'' (The Administrative Palace) is a historic building which was built between 1903\u20131904 to serve as the seat of Suceava City Hall. The building originally had only two sides of the four current sides, and was designed by Viennese architect [[Peter Paul Brang]]. It was designed in the baroque style. Currently, the palace houses the prefecture and the county council of Suceava County.\n\n[[File:Casa_Polon\u0103_din_Suceava4.jpg|thumb|left|The 'Dom Polski' Polish House]]\n\n''Casa Polon\u0103'' (The Polish House) is a building made between 1903\u20131907 by the Polish community in the city of Suceava. The building was designed by architect [[Alojz Friedel]]. During the communist regime, The Polish House was nationalized, and since 1954, it housed ''Ansamblul Artistic Ciprian Porumbescu'' (Ciprian Porumbescu Artistic Ensemble). In 1984 the building was restored, and then hosted a local theatre, until 1990. In 1996, the building was returned to the Polish community of the city.\n\n''Uzina de Ap\u0103'' (The Water Plant) is a set of industrial heritage buildings, designed in 1908 by engineer G. Thiem from [[Leipzig]] and built between 1910\u20131912.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://miesarch.com/work/1112|title=Water Plant, Center for Architecture, Urban Culture and landscape|author=www.miesarch.com|work=Fundaci\u00f3 Mies van der Rohe. 2018|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref> The water plant operated in these buildings between 1912\u20131960, and then it was moved into a modern building. In 2012, in celebration of 100 years since its establishment, in the former water plant buildings there was inaugurated the Centre for Architecture, Urban Culture and Landscape in Suceava.\n\n''Biblioteca Bucovinei I.G. Sbiera'' (I.G. Sbiera Bukovina Library) is the first public library in Suceava, inaugurated on 12 December 1923. It is also the largest library in Suceava County, with over 350,000 bibliographic units. Currently, the library is hosted by two historic buildings located in downtown Suceava and built between 1925\u20131926, respectively 1929\u20131930.\n\n''The County Forestry Department'' in Suceava is an institution which operates in a heritage building located in Areni neighborhood, in the city of Suceava. The building dates from the first half of the 20th century.\n\n''The Unions House'' in Suceava is a heritage building, located in downtown Suceava, which houses the unions offices, along with some shops. The building is also known as Samuil Isopescu House.\n\n''Casa Costin Tarangul'' (Costin Tarangul House) is a heritage house dating from the 19th century (1886). The building is located next to Simion Florea Marian Memorial House, in the center of Suceava.\n\n''Casa Ciprian Porumbescu'' (Ciprian Porumbescu House) is a heritage house dating from the 19th century, where Romanian composer [[Ciprian Porumbescu]] lived and created some of his works. The house is located in Prunului street, downtown Suceava.\n\n''School No. 5 Jean Bart'' in Burdujeni (Suceava) is a school built in 1902 in the village Burdujeni, today a town district of Suceava. The building that houses the school has historic value.\n\n''School No. 6 in Burdujeni-Sat'' (Suceava) is a school built in 1911 in the village Burdujeni, today a town district of Suceava. The building that houses the school has historic value.\n\n''Former Burdujeni Town Hall'' in Suceava is a building that was built in 1902 in the village Burdujeni and initially was the town hall of the locality. In 1926 Burdujeni became a district of Suceava, and so the town hall was abolished. The historic building currently houses the headquarters of Electrica company.\n\n====I\u021bcani neighbourhood====\n\n{{multiple image|perrow = 2|total_width=300\n| image1 = Gara Suceava Nord1.jpg\n| image2 = Poli\u0163ia din I\u0163cani1.jpg\n| image3 = \u0218coala din I\u021bcani1.jpg\n| image4 = Cl\u0103dire din I\u021bcani.jpg\n| footer = Clockwise from left to right: Suceava North railway station, former police station, the old elementary school in I\u021bcani, and a local Austrian-style household.\n}}\n\n[[I\u021bcani]] ({{lang-de|Itzkany}}) is a neighbourhood located several miles northwest of the city centre. Initially established as a small village in the 15th century under the rulership of [[Alex\u0103ndrel of Moldavia]], it subsequently expanded as a German-speaking colony much later, specifically starting in the late 19th century, seeing an influx of German settlers during the [[Josephine colonization]] ({{lang-de|Josephinische Kolonisation}}) which took place in the time of the [[Austrian Empire]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bukovinasociety.org/buko/sitefiles/Talsky-Josef-Heimat-von-gestern-Regional-distribution-of-Germans-in-Bukovina.html|author=www.bukovinasociety.org|work=The Bukovina Society of the Americas|title=The Regional Distribution of the Germans in Bukovina|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bukovinasociety.org/buko/sitefiles/Stephani-Claus-1978-Settlement-of-German-Population-Groups-in-Bukovina-E.html|author=www.bukovinasociety.org|work=The Bukovina Society of the Americas|title=The Golden Bistritz - The Settlement of German Population Groups in Bukovina|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref> [[Suceava North railway station|The north railway station]] (which depicts architectural elements of both [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic revival]] and [[Neo-romanticism|Neo-romanticist]] styles, also the oldest in the city) is situated in this neighbourhood as well.\n\n=== Monuments ===\n\nNear the fortress, in \u0218ipote-Cetate Park, there is an [[equestrian statue]] of Stephen the Great, designed and made by the local sculptor Iftimie B\u00e2rleanu in 1977. The monument has 23 meters in height, being the tallest equestrian statue in Romania. In the city centre there's also a statue dedicated to [[Petru Mu\u0219at]], Prince of Moldavia between 1375\u20131391.\n\n===Religious buildings===\n\n====Romanian Orthodox churches====\n\nOne of the most important cultural sites in Suceava is [[Saint John the New Monastery]] which includes the monumental Church of [[Saint George]], built between 1514 and 1522. The construction began during the reign of voivode [[Bogdan III the One-Eyed]] of Moldavia, after the nearby Mir\u0103u\u021bi Church (the metropolitan cathedral of Moldavia at that moment) was devastated in 1513. The construction was completed by [[Stephen IV of Moldavia]] (also known as \u0218tef\u0103ni\u021b\u0103). The monastery church served as metropolitan cathedral of Moldavia until 1677. It has frescoes painted on the outside, typical of the region, and is one of eight buildings that make up the [[churches of Moldavia]] [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]].<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/598 Churches of Moldavia] at the UNESCO site</ref> Since 1991 Saint John the New Monastery serves as the cathedral of the [[Archdiocese of Suceava and R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]]. Saint John the New<ref>[http://sfantulioancelnou.8k.ro/ sfantulioancelnou.8k.ro] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091227211255/http://sfantulioancelnou.8k.ro/ |date=2009-12-27 }}</ref> was a Moldavian monk who preached during Turkish occupation and was subsequently martyred in Cetatea Alb\u0103, present-day [[Bilhorod-Dnistrovskyi]] in [[Ukraine]]. [[Alexander I of Moldavia]] brought his relics to Suceava in 1402.\n\nMir\u0103u\u021bi Church, dedicated to Saint George, is the oldest religious building in Suceava, founded by [[Petru II of Moldavia]] in late 14th century, in the same period with the Seat Fortress, when he moved the capital from [[Siret]] to Suceava. The church established the city as a see of it. Mir\u0103u\u021bi was the metropolitan cathedral of Moldavia between 1402 and 1522, when the church of Saint John the New Monastery was completed. In 1402, the relics of Saint John the New were transferred to this church from [[Cetatea Alb\u0103]], and then, in 1589 transferred again to the nearby monastery church by voivode [[Peter the Lame]]. The name ''Mir\u0103u\u021bi'' derives from the fact that it was the coronation church of Moldavia until 1522. [[Stephen the Great]] was crowned in here in 1457. After the church was devastated, it was rebuilt in early 17th century, and then, in the 18th century, abandoned.\n\nChurch of [[Saint Demetrius of Thessaloniki|Saint Demetrius]] was founded by [[Peter IV Rare\u0219]], ruler of Moldavia (1527\u20131538, 1541\u20131546), and the son of Stephan the Great. The church was built in 1534\u20131535, with a bell tower added in 1560\u20131561 by Alexandru L\u0103pu\u0219neanu. The bell tower is 40 meters high, being the tallest bell tower in Suceava and a landmark of the city. The church had frescoes painted on the outside, that are still visible on one side wall. The frescoes inside were restored recently. Church of Saint Demetrius is located near the ruins of the former Princely Court of Suceava.\n\n{{multiple image|perrow = 2|total_width=300\n| image1 = M\u0103n\u0103stirea Sf\u00e2ntul Ioan cel Nou35.jpg\n| image2 = Biserica Sf. Dumitru din Suceava34.jpg\n| image3 = Biserica Mirauti27.jpg\n| image4 = Biserica Sf\u00e2ntul Nicolae din Suceava2.jpg\n| footer = Clockwise from left to right: St. John the New Monastery (UNESCO World Heritage site), Church of St. Demetrius, Mir\u0103u\u021bi Church, Church of St. Nicholas.\n}}\n\nFurthermore, there is another old church near these ruins. Church of [[Saint John the Baptist]], also known as Coconilor Church or Domni\u021belor Church, was founded in 1643 by [[Vasile Lupu]], voivode of Moldavia between 1632 and 1653. It has no exterior frescoes and a short bell tower that has its roof linked with the roof above the church. In its early days, the church functioned as a chapel for the Princely Court.\n\nChurch of the Resurrection (located in the proximity of Saint John the New Monastery) dates from 1551, and was founded by Elena Rare\u0219, the wife of voivode Peter IV Rare\u0219. The church has no tower above the [[cella|naos]], its architecture reflecting the urban style of the medieval period. Instead of the bell tower, the church has a [[zvonnitsa]], an architectural form especially used in the [[Russian architecture]] of the 14th\u201317th centuries. Church of the Resurrection was used by the local Roman Catholic community during the Habsburg occupation, and then by the Ruthenian Greek Catholic community, until 1936. It is also known as ''V\u0103scresenia Church'' or ''Elena Doamna'' Church.\n\nChurch of [[Saint Nicholas]] (Pr\u0103jescu) is another religious building in Suceava that features the medieval Moldavian architectural style. The present church was rebuilt by treasurer Nicoar\u0103 Pr\u0103jescu in 1611, during the reign of Constantin Movil\u0103 (1607\u20131611). Throughout its history, the church functioned as a necropolis for the local [[boyar]]s.\n\nBetween the city center and I\u021bcani neighborhood, on the slopes that descend to the [[Suceava (river)|Suceava river valley]], there is Church of the Assumption, another old Romanian Orthodox church, founded in the first half of the 17th century (1639). The church was built on the place where I\u021bcani Monastery existed before. It functioned as a nunnery until late 18th century. Today it is parish church, and has a zvonnitsa similar to that of Church of the Resurrection, located downtown.\n\nIn Burdujeni neighborhood, {{convert|4|km|0|abbr=on}} north-east of the city center, there is Teodoreni Monastery, founded in 1597 by local boyar Teodor Movil\u0103, the elder brother of [[Ieremia Movil\u0103]], ruler of Moldavia (1595\u20131600, 1600\u20131606). Burdujeni village (now a district of Suceava) was established and developed around this monastery. The set of buildings includes Church of Ascension, the bell tower, living quarters for nuns and a surrounding wall. Just {{convert|1|km|1|abbr=on}} north of Teodoreni Monastery, in the old district of Burdujeni, there is Church of the Holy Trinity, founded by archimandrite Filaret Scriban in 1851.\n\nI\u021bcani neighborhood has two Romanian Orthodox churches founded in the first half of the 20th century: Church of the Holy Archangels (built near [[Suceava North railway station]], in 1933\u20131938) and Church of the Holy Apostles (located on [[European route E85]] and built in 1905\u20131908 by the German community of I\u021bcani, initially as a Lutheran church).\n\n[[Church of the Holy Cross, P\u0103tr\u0103u\u021bi|Church of the Holy Cross]], located in [[P\u0103tr\u0103u\u021bi]] village (a few miles north-west of I\u021bcani), was founded in 1487 by Stephen the Great, and is one of the monuments that make up the [[churches of Moldavia]] [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]]. Also not far away from I\u021bcani, there is [[Dragomirna Monastery]], established by clergyman [[Anastasie Crimca]] in 1609. [[Vorone\u021b Monastery]] is located {{convert|40|km|0|abbr=on}} west of Suceava, in the town of [[Gura Humorului]].\n\n====German Roman Catholic and Lutheran churches====\n\n{{multiple image|perrow = 2|total_width=200\n| image1 = Biserica Sf. Ioan Nepomuk din Suceava44.jpg\n| image2 = Biserica Sf. Elisabeta din Itcani15.jpg\n| image3 = Biserica Sf. Apostoli din Itcani10.jpg\n| image4 = Biserica Evanghelic\u0103 din Suceava1.jpg\n| footer = Clockwise from left to right: St. John of Nepomuk Roman Catholic Church, St. Elizabeth Roman Catholic Church,  St. Apostles Lutheran Church, The Evangelical Church.\n}}\n\nDuring the late [[Modern Age]] until the mid 20th century, a sizable [[Bukovina Germans|German]] community lived in Suceava, making up almost a quarter of the total population of the city in the 1900s. They were of both Roman Catholic and Evangelical Lutheran faith given the fact that they had a rather diverse geographic origin from which they initially stemmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bukowinafreunde.de/Neuer%20Ordner/faq/Bukovina%20and%20its%20Bukovina%20Germans.pdf|author=www.bukowinafreunde.de|work=Bukowina Freunde|title=Bukovina and its Bukovina Germans by Willi Kosiul|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://master.cedcsv.ro/cedc/infos/informatica/Minoritatile_conlocuitoare_din_judetul_Suceava/Germanii/germanii.html|author=www.mastercedcsv.ro|work=Minorit\u0103\u021bile conlocuitoare din jude\u021bul Suceava|title=Germanii (in Romanian)|accessdate= 31 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTherefore, these German-speaking colonists who were settled by the Austrian Empire in the city proper can trace their origins most notably from present-day southern [[Germany]], [[Austria]], and [[Bohemia]], both Catholics and Protestants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bukovinasociety.org/buko/sitefiles/Welisch-2002-1.html|author=www.bukovinasociety.org|work=The Bukovina Society of the Americas|title=The History of Bukovina by Dr. Sophie A. Welisch|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref> Several religious buildings that served both aforementioned religious denominations can still be found today both in the city proper and in the [[I\u021bcani]] neighborhood, where a bygone numerous German-speaking community (stemming from contemporary [[Rhineland-Palatinate]] land in [[Germany]]) once lived.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.monitorulsv.ro/Local/2009-08-24/Viata-germanilor-bucovineni-din-Itcanii-Noi|author=www.monitorulsv.ro|work=Monitorul de Suceava|title=Via\u0163a germanilor bucovineni din I\u0163canii Noi|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Armenian Orthodox churches====\n\n[[File:Biserica Sf. Cruce din Suceava.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Church of the Holy Cross]]\n[[File:M\u0103n\u0103stirea Zamca30.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Zamca Monastery]]\n\nIn the past, Suceava used to have an important Armenian community as well. Their cultural and historical legacy is highlighted by a series of well preserved religious buildings that still exist to this today.\n\nThe most representative ecclesiastical landmark established by the local Armenian population is Zamca Monastery (the term Zamca can actually trace its linguistic origin to [[Polish language|Polish]], denoting as such a 'fortified place' and being named this way by [[List of Polish monarchs|King]] [[John III Sobieski|Jan Sobieski]] of [[Crown of the Kingdom of Poland|Poland]] in 1691), a fortified complex of buildings located on a plateau at the western point of the contemporary city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://calatoresc.ro/descopera-orasul-suceava/|author=Isabela|work=c\u0103l\u0103toresc.ro|title=Descoper\u0103 ora\u0219ul Suceava (in Romanian)|date=2 October 2013|accessdate= 28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nZamca Monastery was constructed between 1551 and 1606 and its church is dedicated to Saint Auxentius. Along with the church, the monastery includes several buildings made of stone and a defensive wall that surrounds the whole medieval complex.\n\nBetween Zamca Monastery and the city center there are two more Armenian Orthodox churches. Church of Saint Simon (also known as The Red Tower Church because of its bell tower) was founded in 1513. The bell tower was constructed in 1551.\n\nThe church has an old Armenian cemetery in the proximity and a chapel that was built in 1902 (Pruncul Chapel). Church of the Holy Cross was established in 1521 and was renovated several times in its history. The Armenian parsonage is located near the church, along with several old tomb stones.\n\nHagigadar Monastery is another medieval complex built by the local Armenians. It was founded in 1512\u20131513, and is located on the south-western proximity of the city, on a valley near [[European route E85]].\n\n==Tourism==\n\nIn the past few years Suceava started to evolve more rapidly. The most important sights in the town date from its time as a princely capital (i.e. the Middle Ages). There are numerous museums in the city proper including, most notably, the Bucovina History Museum, the Bucovina Village Museum,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://muzeulbucovinei.ro/muzeul-satului-bucovinean/|author=www.monitorulsv.ro|work=Muzeul Bucovinei|title=Muzeul Satului Bucovinean|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref> Bucovina Ethnographic Museum (housed in an inn dating back to the 17th century),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orasulsuceava.ro/unde-iesim/obiective-turistice/muzee/muzeul-etnografic-hanul-domnesc/|work=Ora\u0219ul Suceava|title=Muzeul Etnografic Hanul Domnesc (in Romanian)|accessdate= 28 September 2018}}</ref> or the Natural History Museum.\n\n== Sports ==\n\n=== Football ===\n\n[[File:Stadionul Areni7.jpg|thumb|right|Areni Stadium stand]]\n\n[[ACS Foresta Suceava]] ({{lang-ro|Asocia\u021bia Club Sportiv Foresta Suceava}}), formerly known as Rapid CFR Suceava, is the football team that currently represents the city of Suceava in the third tier of the Romanian football system, more specifically in [[Liga III]].\n\nIn the past, the city has also had other significant football clubs competing in either [[Liga I]] or Liga II (depending on their level of performance) such as [[CSM Suceava]], [[FC Cetatea Suceava]], or [[Foresta F\u0103lticeni|Foresta Suceava]] (the latter one being initially based in the city of [[F\u0103lticeni]] from the same county). The city also used to have another Liga III side called [[Sporting Suceava]], but due to financing reasons the club had subsequently went bankrupt and ceased playing.\n\nAll the major sporting events are hosted on the [[Stadionul Areni|Areni Stadium]], a multi-purpose stadium in Suceava. It is currently the home ground of ACS Foresta Suceava and can hold up to 12,500 people. The stadium was initially opened in 1963 as the \"''Municipal Stadium''\".\n\n=== Handball ===\n\n[[CSU Suceava|CS Universitatea Bucovina Suceava]] is the city's men's [[handball]] team which currently competes in the [[Liga Na\u021bional\u0103 (men's handball)|Romanian Handball League]] ({{lang-ro|Liga Na\u021bional\u0103}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://csusuceava.ro/echipa/istoric/|title=Echipa - Istoric|publisher=csusuceava.ro|access-date=31 May 2011|language=Romanian|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830072422/http://csusuceava.ro/echipa/istoric/|archive-date=30 August 2013|df=}}</ref> It was founded in 2002 and it started playing in the first tier of the Romanian handball system in 2006. In 2011 it achieved its greatest performance to date, namely finishing 3rd in the national handball division.\n\n==Schooling and education==\nThe main university of the city (and also of the entire county) is the [[\u0218tefan cel Mare University of Suceava]] established in 1990, which has 10,138 students to date.\n\n[[File:Universitatea din Suceava1.jpg|thumb|\u015etefan cel Mare University of Suceava]]\nThe most prominent high schools with theoretical pathway are as follows:\n\n'''National College \"Mihai Eminescu\" Suceava'''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cn-eminescu.ro/| title=Colegiul Na\u021bional \"Mihai Eminescu\" din Suceava| accessdate= 17 June 2018}}</ref>\n*Named after the most well-known Moldavian and Romanian poet, [[Mihai Eminescu]]\n*Main study offers are: Social Sciences, Mathematics and Informatics, Philology.\n\n'''National College \"Petru Rare\u0219\" Suceava'''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cnprsv.ro/| title=Coleiul Na\u021bional \"Petru Rare\u0219\" din Suceava| accessdate= 17 June 2018}}</ref>\n*Named after the voievod of Moldavia, [[Peter IV Rare\u015f]]\n*Main study offers are: English, Philology, Mathematics and Informatics.\n\n[[File:Liceul \u0218tefan cel Mare din Suceava.jpg|thumb|\u0218tefan cel Mare National College]]\n\n'''National College \"\u0218tefan cel Mare\" Suceava'''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cnstefancelmare.ro| title=Colegiul Na\u021bional \"\u0218tefan cel Mare\" din Suceava| accessdate= 17 June 2018}}</ref>\n*Named after the prince of Moldavia between the years 1457 and 1504, [[Stephen III of Moldavia]]\n*Main study offers are: Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Informatics.\n\n'''Economical College \"Dimitre Cantemir\" Suceava'''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://master.cedcsv.ro/cedc/| title=Colegiul Economic \"Dimitrie Cantemir\" Suceava| accessdate= 17 June 2018}}</ref>\n*Named after the twice Prince of Moldavia and the famous writer of the Descriptio Moldavie, [[Dimitrie Cantemir]].\n*It is the only economics high-school in Suceava. \n*Main study offers are Tourism, Gastronomy, Alimentation, Economy, Countability and Trade.\n*The main profile which the school promovates is the Technical profile.\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Air===\n\n[[File:Aerogara Suceava.jpg|thumb|right|Suceava \u015etefan cel Mare International Airport - new TWR and main terminal building in 2015.]]\n\nSuceava is served by the [[Suceava International Airport|Suceava International \"\u015etefan cel Mare\" Airport]] (SCV), located {{convert|12|km|abbr=on}} east of the city centre, in the small town of [[Salcea]].<ref name=\"loc\">[http://www.aeroportsuceava.ro/en/2016-01-29-19-50-13/2016-01-29-19-55-57.html LRSV location] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325173110/http://aeroportsuceava.ro/en/2016-01-29-19-50-13/2016-01-29-19-55-57.html |date=2016-03-25 }}</ref> The airport initially opened in 1962 when commercial services started with [[TAROM]], the oldest operating Romanian airline.<ref name=\"history\">[http://www.aeroportsuceava.ro/en/2012-01-04-13-30-45/istoric About Suceava Airport] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151011162947/http://www.aeroportsuceava.ro/en/2012-01-04-13-30-45/istoric |date=2015-10-11 }}</ref> In 1963, the runway was paved, and an apron was built. Services by TAROM were discontinued in 2001, but resumed in 2004. During this period, the airport was served only by [[Angel Airlines (Romania)|Angel Airlines]]. In March 2005, the airport was renamed ''\u0218tefan cel Mare Airport'', and opened to international traffic.\n\nIn 2013, Suceava International Airport started a plan (worth {{c.}} \u20ac39 million) to rebuild and extend the old runway of {{convert|1800|m|abbr=on|0}}, to construct a new control tower and to install a new [[Instrument landing system|ILS system]].<ref>[http://www.aeroportsuceava.ro/documente/comunicate/9-08-2013.pdf Suceava Airport press release]</ref> In August 2013, the construction works commenced,<ref>[http://www.obiectivdesuceava.ro/local/lucrarile-la-aeroportul-sucevei-au-demarat-fara-surle-si-trambite/ Lucr\u0103rile la aeroportul Sucevei au demarat] {{in lang|ro}}</ref> and on 12 January 2014, the airport closed in order to allow the runway works to resume. The old concrete runway was completely removed, and a new runway, made out of asphalt, was constructed. \n\nOn 25 October 2015, the airport was officially reopened.<ref>[http://www.agerpres.ro/social/2015/10/25/aeroportul-suceava-deschis-traficului-aerian-intern-si-international-18-19-08 Aeroportul Suceava deschis traficului aerian intern \u0219i interna\u021bional] {{in lang|ro}}</ref> As of 2018, Suceava International Airport had an annual traffic of 353,280 passengers, a local record thus far, making it the [[List of the busiest airports in Romania|8th busiest airport in Romania]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Traficul pe Aeroportul \u201e\u0218tefan cel Mare\u201d Suceava a atins \u00een 2017 un record istoric|publisher=newsbucovina.ro|url=https://www.newsbucovina.ro/actualitate/212366/traficul-pe-aeroportul-stefan-cel-mare-suceava-atins-2017-un-record-istoric-de-261-000-de-pasageri-iar-2018-se-estimeaza-o-crestere-cu-peste-20-la-suta-prin-introducerea-de}}</ref>\n\n==Natives==\n\n{{Category see also|People from Suceava}}\n\n{{Collapsible list|title=Intellectuals and artists|\n{{Div col}}\n* [[:de:Marius Babias|Marius Babias]], art critic, author, and curator (director of [[:de:Neuer Berliner Kunstverein|Neuer Berliner Kunstverein]] since 2008)\n* [[Iosif Berman]], photographer and journalist during the [[interwar period]]\n* [[Eugeniu Botez]] (nom de plume ''Jean Bart''), writer\n* [[:ro: Stela Cheptea|Stela Cheptea]], historian and medievalist\n* [[Vladimir G\u0103itan]], actor\n* [[Norman Manea]], writer and intellectual\n* [[:ro: Ioan Neme\u0219|Ioan Neme\u0219]], physicist and biologist\n* [[:de:George Ostafi|George Ostafi]], abstract painter\n* [[Gheorghe Panaiteanu Bardasare]], painter\n* [[:ro: Nicolae Picu|Nicolae Picu]], violinist\n* [[Pamfil Polonic]], archaeologist and topographer\n* [[:ro:Ioana Rosto\u0219|Ioana Rosto\u0219]] (nom de plume ''Jane Rostos''), writer\n* [[:de:Ludwig Adolf Staufe-Simiginowicz|Ludwig Adolf Staufe-Simiginowicz]], poet and German language teacher\n{{div col end}}\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|title=Sportsmen|\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Daniel B\u0103lan]], football player and coach\n* [[Petru B\u0103lan]], rugby union footballer\n* [[Mugur Bolohan|Cristian Mugur Bolohan]], former football player and coach\n* [[Alexandru Buziuc]], football player\n* [[Ionu\u021b Dimofte]], rugby union football player\n* [[Irina Dorneanu]], Olympic rower\n* [[Iulian Dumitra\u0219]], rugby union football player\n* [[Dorin Goian]], former football player and coach\n* [[Lucian Goian]], football player\n* [[C\u0103t\u0103lin Golofca]], football player\n* [[Lidia Havri\u0219tiuc]], football player\n* [[Aleksandru Longher]], football player\n* [[Paul Mateciuc]], football player\n* [[Cosmin Pa\u0219covici]], former football player\n* [[Anca Poloco\u0219er]], handball player\n* [[Doru Popadiuc]], football player\n* [[Mihai Roman]], football player\n* [[Tiberiu Serediuc]], football player\n* [[Ovidiu Slu\u0219ariuc]], former rugby union football player\n* [[Sonia Ursu-Kim]], basketball player\n{{div col end}}\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|title=Clergymen|\n* [[Dosoftei|Dimitrie Baril\u0103]], 17th century [[Moldavia]]n [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan]], scholar, poet, and translator\n* [[Iosif Bobulescu]], 19th century bishop\n* [[Anastasie Crimca]], 16th century [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Eastern orthodox]] clergyman, calligrapher, [[Illuminated manuscript|illuminator]], and writer\n* [[Peter Mogila]], 17th century theologian\n* [[Shotzer Rebbe|Shulem Moskovitz]], [[chasidic]] [[Rebbe]]\n* [[Filaret Scriban]], 19th century theologian\n* [[Meir Shapiro]], [[Hasidic]] [[rabbi]] and [[rosh yeshiva]]\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|title=Politicians|\n* [[Luca Arbore]], 15th\u201316th century Moldavian boyar, diplomat, and statesman\n* [[Cristian Adomni\u021bei]], former PNL Minister of Education (2007\u20132008)\n* [[Eugen Bejinariu]], former PSD acting [[Prime Minister of Romania|Prime Minister]] (2004)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Founding of Moldavia|Foundation of Moldavia]]\n* [[List of rulers of Moldavia]]\n* [[Churches of Moldavia|Medieval churches of Moldavia]]\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Romania}}\n\n=== Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities ===\nSuceava is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n* {{flagicon|PRC}} [[Guizhou]], [[China]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.monitorulsv.ro/Local/2009-07-04/Sucevenii-s-au-infratit-cu-chinezii-din-Guizhou|title=Sucevenii s-au \u00eenfr\u0103\u0163it cu chinezii din Guizhou|author=www.monitorulsv.ro|date= 4 July 2009|work=Monitorul de Suceava|accessdate= 9 June 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|ISR}} [[Haifa]], [[Israel]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.monitorulsv.ro/Local/2010-04-08/Suceava-a-inceput-demersurile-de-infratire-cu-orasul-israelian-Haifa|title=Suceava a \u00eenceput demersurile de \u00eenfr\u0103\u0163ire cu ora\u015ful israelian Haifa|author=www.monitorulsv.ro|work=Monitorul de Suceava|date = 8 April 2010|accessdate= 13 June 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Laval, Mayenne|Laval]], [[France]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsme.ro/administratie/suceava-infratita-cu-orasul-francez-laval.html|title=Suceava \u00eenfr\u0103\u021bit\u0103 cu ora\u0219ul francez Laval|author=www.newsme.ro|date= 20 October 2010|work=newsMe|accessdate= 9 June 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|POL}} [[Sosnowiec]], [[Poland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primariasv.ro/portal/suceava/portal.nsf/684A6C3ACAE00E99C2257BEC0023E121/$FILE/Orasul_Sosnowiec_Polonia.pdf|title=Ora\u0219ul Sosnowiec \u2013 Polonia|author=www.primariasv.ro|work=Prim\u0103ria Municipiului Suceava|accessdate= 9 June 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|MDA}} [[Soroca]], [[Moldova|Republic of Moldova]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://radiochisinau.md/maluri-de-prut-la-630-de-ani-de-la-prima-atestare-documentara-suceava-se-infrateste-cu-soroca-doua-orasecetati-cu-legaturi-istorice-profunde---63140.html|title=Maluri de Prut: La 630 de ani de la prima atestare documentar\u0103, Suceava se \u00eenfr\u0103\u021be\u0219te cu Soroca. Dou\u0103 ora\u0219e-cet\u0103\u021bi cu leg\u0103turi istorice profunde|author=Radio Chi\u0219in\u0103u |date= 8 February 2018|work=Radio Chi\u0219in\u0103u|accessdate= 10 February 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|UKR}} [[Chernivtsi]], [[Ukraine]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primariasv.ro/portal/suceava/portal.nsf/684A6C3ACAE00E99C2257BEC0023E121/$FILE/Orasul_Cernauti_Ucraina.pdf|title=Regiunea Cern\u0103u\u0163i este situat\u0103 \u00een zona Mun\u0163ilor Carpa\u0163i din sud-vestul Ucrainei|author=www.primariasv.ro|work=Prim\u0103ria Municipiului Suceava|accessdate= 9 June 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[United States]]\n|}\n\n=== Regional, cultural, and economic partnerships ===\n\nIn addition to the official town/city twinning, the city of Suceava shares a series of regional, cultural, and economic partnerships with the following:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://primariasv.ro/portal/suceava/portal.nsf/AllByUNID/000011BE?OpenDocument|title=Prim\u0103ria Suceava - Despre ora\u0219ul Suceava (in Romanian)}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n* {{flagicon|DEU}} {{flagicon|Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg}} {{flagicon|Bayern}} [[Germany]], [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] and [[Bavaria|Bayern]] - economic, cultural, and touristic contacts with the historical region of [[Swabia]] ({{lang-de|Schwaben}})<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.romaniajournal.ro/ambassador-cord-meier-klodt-german-investors-are-looking-for-new-opportunities-in-romania/|title=Ambassador Cord Meier-Klodt: German investors are looking for new opportunities in Romania|work=The Romania Journal|author=Anca Bernovici|date=25 May 2018|accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Denmark]] - local development partnership with the city of [[Aalborg]], [[North Denmark Region|North Jutland]]\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Italy]] - local development partnership with the city of [[Naples]], [[Campania]]\n* {{flagicon|UK}} [[United Kingdom]] - local development partnership with the city of [[Liverpool]], [[North West England]]\n* {{flagicon|FRA}} [[France]] - local development partnership with the city of [[Lyon]], [[Auvergne-Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]]\n|}\n\n=== Consulates ===\n\n* {{flagicon|UKR}} [[Ukraine]] - Consulate-general\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Palatul Administrativ din Suceava18.jpg|The Administrative Palace (view of the front fa\u00e7ade)\nFile:Palatul de Finante din Suceava8.jpg|The Palace of Finance\nFile:Imagine aerian\u0103 a Palatului de Justi\u0163ie (vedere dinspre Aleea Anastasie Crimca).JPG|The Justice Palace in the city centre\nFile:Spitalul vechi din Suceava3.jpg|The Old Hospital\nFile:Gara Burdujeni.jpg|Burdujeni railway station in wintertime\nFile:Liceul de Art\u0103 din Suceava4.jpg|[[Ciprian Porumbescu]] Art College (former German-language gymnasium)\nFile:Suceava_fortress_19.jpg|Downtown Suceava, as seen from the medieval Seat Fortress (December, 2005)\nFile:View on Suceava (Romania) from Fortess.jpg|Downtown Suceava, as seen from the medieval Seat Fortress (August, 2009)\nFile:Piata 22 Decembrie din Suceava3.jpg|22 December square in downtown Suceava\nFile:Imagine aerian\u0103 a Cet\u0103\u021bii de Scaun a Sucevei.jpg|Aerial view of the Seat Fortress (June, 2015)\nFile:Suczawa twierdza.jpg|The Seat Fortress (August, 2009)\nFile:Suceava_fortress_(by_Pudelek).jpg|Panoramic view of the Seat Fortress of Suceava as seen in August, 2016\nFile:Statuia lui Petru I Mu\u0219at din Suceava2.jpg|Statue of Petru Mu\u0219at, Prince of Moldavia (between 1375\u20131391)\nFile:Suceava_-_Stauia_lui_Stefan_Cel_Mare.jpg|The equestrian statue of Stephen III of Moldavia\nFile:Hotelul Bucovina din Suceava1.jpg|Hotel Bucovina\nFile:Bloc Bd. 1 Decembrie 1918 din Suceava.jpg|Apartment blocks on the 1 December 1918 boulevard\nFile:Bloc Turn Strada Victoriei din Suceava.jpg|Renovated apartment block on Victory street\nFile:Turnul_IFA2.jpg|IFA Tower, the city's tallest structure (with a total height surpassing 200 metres)\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Suceava}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Suceava}}\n* [http://www.primariasv.ro Suceava City Hall Official Site]\n* [https://suceava.media Suceava Media]\n* [https://suceava.photos Suceava Photos]\n* [https://suceava.travel Suceava Travel]\n* [https://suceava.website Suceava Website]\n\n{{Suceava County}}\n{{Cities in Romania}}\n{{RoJudCapitals}}{{Castles in Romania}}\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Capitals of Romanian counties]]\n[[Category:Place names of Hungarian origin in Romania]]\n[[Category:Castles in Romania]]\n[[Category:Former capitals of Romania]]\n[[Category:Bukovina]]\n[[Category:Duchy of Bukovina]]\n[[Category:Localities in Southern Bukovina]]\n[[Category:\u021ainutul Suceava]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Suceava County]]\n[[Category:Suceava| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|\nofficial_name=Suceava\n| settlement_type = City\n|image_skyline={{nowrap|[[File:Palatul Administrativ din Suceava12.jpg|260px]]<br />[[File:Cl\u0103direa Palatului de Justi\u021bie din Suceava1.jpg|130px]][[File:Muzeul Judetean din Suceava11.jpg|130px]]<br />[[File:Gara Burdujeni1.jpg|130px]][[File:Cetatea de Scaun a Sucevei17.jpg|130px]]<br />[[File:M\u0103n\u0103stirea Sf\u00e2ntul Ioan cel Nou26.jpg|x92px]][[File:Biserica Sf. Apostoli din Itcani8.jpg|x92px]][[File:Biserica Sf\u00e2ntul Ioan Nepomuk din Suceava.jpg|x92px]]}}\n|image_caption = Left to right: the Administrative Palace, Palace of Justice, Bukovina History Museum, Burdujeni Train Station, The Medieval Seat Fortress, St. John the New Monastery, St. Apostles Church in I\u0163cani, St. John of Nepomuk Church\n| image_shield = ROU SV Suceava CoA.png\n|map_caption            = Location in Suceava County\n|image_map              = Suceava jud Suceava.png\n| pushpin_map             = Romania#Europe\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location of Suceava\n|coordinates  = {{coord|47|39|05|N|26|15|20|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{ROU}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Counties of Romania|County]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Subdivisions of Romania|Status]]\n|\nsubdivision_name1=[[Suceava County]]\n|\nsubdivision_name2={{Autolink|County capital}}\n|leader_party=[[National Liberal Party (Romania)|PNL]]\n|leader_title = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name=Ion Lungu<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|\n| area_total_km2            = 52.10\n| area_land_km2             =\n| area_water_km2            =\n| area_metro_km2            = 473.29\n|population_as_of  = {{Romania metadata Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n|population_total  = {{Romania metadata Wikidata|population_total}} \n|population_footnotes = {{Romania metadata Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n|population_density_km2=auto\n| pop_est_as_of             = 2018\n| population_est            = 124,161 {{increase}}\n| pop_est_footnotes         = <ref name=\"INSSE 2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-esential-23123474-harta-interactiva-cati-mai-suntem-romania-populatia-fiecare-judet-fiecare-municipiu-din-tara.htm| title= HART\u0102 INTERACTIV\u0102 - C\u00e2\u021bi mai suntem \u00een Rom\u00e2nia? Popula\u021bia \u00een fiecare jude\u021b \u0219i \u00een fiecare municipiu din \u021bar\u0103|date=6 May 2019|accessdate = 6 May 2019|publisher = [[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|INSSE]]|language=Romanian}}</ref>\n| population_metro          = 176,016<ref name=\"luz\">{{cite web|url= http://www.insse.ro/cms/sites/default/files/field/publicatii/populatia_romaniei_pe_localitati_la_1ianuarie2016_0.pdf#page120| title=Population on 1 January by age groups and sex - functional urban areas | accessdate=29 October 2017 | publisher=[[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|INSSE]]|language=Romanian}}</ref>\n| population_note           =\n|\nwebsite=http://www.primariasv.ro/\n|timezone=[[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset=+2\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n|\n|\n|\n||\n||\nblank_name=[[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n|\nblank_info=[[Humid continental climate#Mild/cool summer subtype|Dfb]]\n|\n}}\n\n'''Suceava''' ({{IPA-ro|su\u02c8t\u0283e\u032fava|lang}}, {{lang-de|Suczawa}}) is the largest city and the seat of [[Suceava County]], situated in the historical region of [[Moldavia]], north-eastern [[Romania]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/place/Suceava-county-Romania| title=County of Suceava| work=Encyclopaedia Britannica|accessdate=23 April, 2020}}</ref> and at the crossroads of [[Central Europe|Central]] and [[Eastern Europe]] respectively.<ref name=\"books.google.co.uk\">Klaus Peter Berger, [https://books.google.com/books?id=gEeP9NY2qGkC&pg=PA132&dq=Bukovina+part+of++%22Central+Europe%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=aDHHT7-aCYee8gOV4Iz5DQ&ved=0CDkQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=partof%20Central%20Europe&f=false The Creeping Codification of the New Lex Mercatoria], Kluwer Law International, 2010, p. 132</ref> During the late [[Middle Ages]], more specifically from 1388 to 1564, the city was the third capital of the [[Moldavia|Principality of Moldavia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rri.ro/de_de/suceava_die_geschichtsbeladene_stadt_in_der_bukowina-2542507|author=Daniel Onea, Adina Olaru|work=Radio Rom\u00e2nia Interna\u021bional|title=Suceava \u2013 die geschichtsbeladene Stadt in der Bukowina (in German)|date=27 January 2016|accessdate= 1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theculturetrip.com/europe/romania/articles/the-10-most-beautiful-towns-in-romania|author=Lani Seelinger|work=The Culture Trip|title=The 10 Most Beautiful Towns In Romania|accessdate= 28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1775 and 1918, Suceava was controlled by the [[Habsburg Monarchy]], first as part of its [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]], then became the third most populous urban settlement of the [[Duchy of Bukovina]] ({{lang-de|Herzogtum Bukowina}}),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philhist.uni-augsburg.de/lehrstuehle/volkskunde/Exkursionen/Ukraine/Cz_Bukowina-Deutsche|author=Alexander Weidle|work=University of Augsburg|title=Bukowina Deutsche (in German)|date=10 December 2017|accessdate= 1 October 2018}}</ref> a constituent province of the [[Austrian Empire]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phdthesis.uaic.ro/PhDThesis/%C8%9Aurca%C8%99,%20Ioan,%20Lucian,%20Macarie,%20German%20Language%20and%20Culture%20in%20Southern%20Bukovina-%20The%20Disappearance%20of%20a%20Cultural%20Enclave.pdf|author=\u021aurca\u0219, Ioan, Lucian, Macarie|work=Abstract of PhD thesis|title=German Language and Culture in Southern Bukovina. The Disappearance of a Cultural Enclave|accessdate= 1 October 2018}}</ref> and subsequently a crown land within [[Austria-Hungary]]. It was only surpassed by [[Chernivtsi|Cern\u0103u\u021bi]] ({{lang-de|Czernowitz}}) and [[R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]] ({{lang-de|Radautz}}), both located to the north. Furthermore, thanks to its diverse ethnic background during the Modern Age, Austrian architect Rudolf Gassauer stated that the city of Suceava could have well been perceived as a 'miniature Austria'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dragusanul.ro/marturia-lui-rudolf-gassauer/|author=Dragu\u0219anul.ro|work=Dr\u0103gu\u0219anul|title=M\u0103rturia lui Rudolf Gassauer (in Romanian)|accessdate= 8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, Suceava was an important, strategically-located commercial border town with the then [[Romanian Old Kingdom]] ({{lang-de|Altreich}}). It received a large influx of [[German language|German]]-speaking settlers in the process of the [[Josephine colonization]] ({{lang-de|Josephinische Siedlung}}). This community has since dwindled to a very small number.<ref>{{cite web|title=Portr\u00e4t der Deutschen Minderheit - Geschichte zum Nachh\u00f6ren (in German) |work=Pausen Radio |author= www.pausenradio.net |url= http://pausenradio.net/wpress/?p=1429 |date=25 October 2015 |accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Geschichte einer Minderheit noch nicht zu Ende geschrieben (in German) |work= Allgemeine Deutsche Zeitung f\u00fcr Rum\u00e4nien, www.adz.ro |url= http://www.adz.ro/artikel/artikel/geschichte-einer-minderheit-noch-nicht-zu-ende-geschrieben |author=Robert Tari |date=20 September 2015 |accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of [[World War I]], after 1918, [[Union of Bukovina with the Kingdom of Romania|along with the rest of Bukovina]], Suceava became part of the then newly enlarged [[Kingdom of Romania]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://europecentenary.eu/declaration-of-union-of-bukovina-with-the-kingdom-of-romania| title=Declaration of Union of Bukovina with the Kingdom of Romania (in English)|work=Europe Centenary|date=13 August 2018| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> After the end of [[World War II]], the city slowly underwent a process of forced Communist urbanization which increased its population about tenfold throughout the decades before the [[Romanian Revolution|1989 revolution]]. It became a municipality ({{lang-ro|municipiu}}) in 1968.\n\n=={{anchor|Names and etymology}}Names and etymology==\n{{see also|Names of Suceava in different languages}}\n\nMoldavian chronicler [[Grigore Ureche]] presumed the name of the city came from the [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] ''Sz\u0171csv\u00e1r'', which is combined of the words ''sz\u0171cs'' (furrier, skinner) and ''v\u00e1r'' (castle). This was taken over by [[Dimitrie Cantemir]], who in his work ''[[:s:la:Descriptio Moldaviae|Descriptio Moldaviae]]'' gave the very same explanation of the origin of the city's name, however, there are neither historical nor vernacular evidences for this. According to another theory, the city bears the name of the [[Suceava (river)|river]] with the same name, that is supposed to be of [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] origin.<ref name=debrecen>{{cite book |last=Hoffmann |first=Istv\u00e1n |title=Helyn\u00e9vt\u00f6rt\u00e9neti tanulm\u00e1nyok 3. |year=2008 |publisher=University of Debrecen, Department of Hungarian Linguistics |location=Debrecen |isbn=978-963-473-115-3|page=212}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Old High German|Old German]] ({{lang-de|Altdeutsch}}) the city was known as ''Sedschopff'',<ref>[[Johann Schiltberger]]. ''[https://archive.org/details/hansschiltberge00langgoog Hans Schiltbergers Reisebuch]'' T\u00fcbingen, Litterarischer Verein in Stuttgart, 1885, p. 111</ref> in [[German language|High German]] sources it can be found under such variations as ''Sotschen'',<ref>Peter Kosta (Hrsg.): Eine russische Kosmographie aus dem 17. Jahrhundert: sprachwissenschaftliche Analyse mit Textedition und Faksimile, Otto Sagner, 1982. {{ISBN|3-87690-200-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.burgenwelt.org/rumaenien/lokal/lokal2-suceava.php#links|work = Burgenwelt| author = Andy Winkler| date = 13 February 2015| title = Jude\u021bul Suceava, Kreis Suceava, Burgen und andere Wehrbauten (in German)| accessdate = 6 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.burgenwelt.org/rumaenien/suceava/object.php#historie|work = Burgenwelt| author = Andy Winkler| date = 13 February 2015| title = Cetatea de Scaun, Festung Suceava (in German)| accessdate = 6 March 2020}}</ref>''Sutschawa'', or ''Suczawa'', in Hungarian as ''Szucs\u00e1va''<ref name=debrecen /> ({{IPA-hu|\u02c8sut\u0361\u0283a\u02d0v\u0252|}}) or ''Sz\u0151csv\u00e1s\u00e1r'', in [[Polish language|Polish]] as  ''Suczawa'', in Ukrainian as ''\u0421\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0432\u0430'' (Su\u010dava), while in [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]] as \u05e9\u05d0\u05b8\u05e5 ({{IPA-yi|\u0283\u0254ts|}}).<ref>For Yiddish spelling and pronunciation, see [http://shotzer.com/zope/home/en/1/homepage_en/ \"Shotzer - the book of the Jews of Suceava\"] {{ISBN|965-7226-16-3}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Franz Xavier Knapp - Gr\u00e4nz-Stadt Suczarva.jpg|thumb|left|Artist's impression of the city Suceava from 1867 by Austrian painter [[:de:Franz Xaver Knapp|Franz Xaver Knapp.]]]]\n[[File:1 \u0421\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0432\u0430.jpg|thumb|left|Artist's impression of the city of Suceava from 1870 by Austrian painter [[:de:Franz Xaver Knapp|Franz Xaver Knapp.]]]]\n[[File:Ceausescu la Suceava 1970.jpg|thumb|right|Former Communist dictator [[Nicolae Ceau\u0219escu]] visting Suceava in 1970.]]\n\nThe present-day territory of the city of Suceava and the adjacent surroundings were already inhabited since the [[Paleolithic]] period. Stemming from the late [[Ancient history|Antiquity]], there are also traces of [[Dacian tribe|Dacian]] [[oppidum]] of the 2nd century.\n\nIn stark contrast to several [[historical regions of Romania]] (most notably [[Transylvania]] and [[Oltenia]]), Suceava (along with the entire region of Bukovina for that matter) was not conquered by the legions of the [[Roman Empire]] and consequently was one of the lands of the [[Free Dacians|Free Dacian tribes]] during the late Ancient Age. Nonetheless, according to [[Ptolemy]], at that time in the region also dwelled two likely [[Celts|Celtic]]-speaking tribes, specifically the [[Anartes]] and the [[Taurisci]],<ref>Ptolemy III.8.5</ref> as well as the [[Germanic peoples|Germanic]] [[Bastarnae]], who have also been attested there.<ref name=\"Barrington Map 22\">Barrington Map 22</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Fall of the Western Roman Empire|fall of Rome]] and during the [[Migration Period]], the predominantly [[Carpi (people)|Carpiani]] population was successively invaded by [[East Germanic tribes|East Germanic peoples]] (such as the [[Goths]] or the [[Gepids]]), [[Huns]], [[Slavs]], [[Hungarians|Magyars]], [[Pechenegs]], and ultimately [[Cumans]]. During the [[Late Middle Ages]], the city of Suceava was the capital of the [[Principality of Moldavia]] and the main residence of the Moldavian [[List of rulers of Moldavia|princes]] for nearly two centuries (namely between 1388 and 1564).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/place/Suceava-Romania| title=Encyclopaedia Britannica - City of Suceava}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://muzeulbucovinei.ro/en/arhive/11738| title= Muzeul Bucovinei - Princely Fortress of Suceava (in Romanian)| author=Muzeul Bucovinei}}</ref>\n\nThe city was the capital of the lands of [[Stephen III of Moldavia|Stephen the Great]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bukowinafreunde.de/geschichte.html |title= Die Bukowina |author=Bukowina Freunde |work= www.bukowinafreunde.de |language= German |accessdate= 1 October 2018}}</ref> one of the pivotal figures in Romanian history, who died in Suceava in 1504. During the rule of [[Alexandru L\u0103pu\u0219neanu]], the seat was moved to [[Ia\u0219i]] in 1565 and Suceava failed to become the capital again. [[Michael the Brave]] captured the city in 1600 during the [[Moldavian Magnate Wars]] as he became the ruler of [[Wallachia]], [[Moldavia]], and [[Transylvania]], but he was defeated the same year.\n\n[[File:Platforma_industriala_Valea_Sucevei.jpg|thumb|right|Suceava valley industrial platform, bird's-eye view taken at some point during the 1960s.]]\n\nTogether with the rest of [[Bukovina]] ({{lang-de|Buchenland}}), Suceava was under the rule of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] (and, later, the [[Austrian Empire]] as well as [[Austria-Hungary]]) from 1775 to 1918 (with the border of the Habsburg domains passing just south-east of the city).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goethe.de/resources/files/pdf134/minoritatea-germana-din-romania1.pdf| work= Goethe Institut| title=Minoritatea german\u0103 din Rom\u00e2nia de Winfried Ziegler (in Romanian)| accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref> During the late 19th century and early 20th century, the city was the third largest in the [[Duchy of Bukovina]], after [[Chernivtsi|Cern\u0103u\u021bi]] and [[R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]].\n\nIn 1918, the city of Suceava (as well as the entire region of Bukovina) became part of what is known as '[[Greater Romania]]', after an overwhelming vote of the German, Romanian, and Polish representatives of the [[General Congress of Bukovina]]. Throughout the interwar period, Suceava undergone further infrastructural development within the then enlarged [[Kingdom of Romania]]. Moreover, from an administrative point of view, it had also briefly belonged to [[\u021ainutul Suceava]] (between 1938 and 1940), one of the 10 lands established during [[Carol II of Romania|King Carol II of Romania]]'s reign.\n\nSubsequently, from the 1950s onwards (along with the onset of [[Socialist Republic of Romania|Communism]]), Suceava was heavily industrialized and a significant series of historical buildings from its old city centre were demolished in order for [[Plattenbau]]-like blocks of flats to be constructed at the orders of the [[Romanian Communist Party|Communist officials]].<ref>The Rough Guide to Romania, {{ISBN|978-1-84353-326-9}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n\n[[File:Around Suceava, Romania (10766493523).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Arable land near the city of Suceava, as seen from above.]]\n\nThe city covers two types of geographical areas, the hills (of which the highest is Zamca Hill) and the meadows of the [[Suceava (river)|Suceava]] river valley.<ref>[https://civitas.eu/cs/content/suceava Suceava's profile on www.civitas.eu]</ref> The unique setting of the urban settlement includes two groves, Zamca and \u0218ipote, which are both located within the city limits. Burdujeni, one of the neighbourhoods, is connected to the rest of the city by a prominent avenue, which makes the neighbourhood appear to be a separate [[satellite town]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Austrian and Romanian census data and/or official estimates\n| 1910 | 10,955\n| 1912 | 11,229\n| 1930 | 17,028\n| 1948 | 10,123\n| 1956 | 20,949\n| 1966 | 37,697\n| 1977 | 62,715\n| 1992 | 114,462\n| 2002 | 106,138\n| 2011 | 92,121\n| 2016 | 116,404\n| 2018 | 124,161\n}}\n\nIn 1910, when the city was still under Imperial Austrian administration, the total population amounted to 10,955 inhabitants. Of those, 61.5% declared their native language to be [[German language|German]] (i.e. ''Hochdeutsch''), followed by [[Romanian language|Romanian]] with 25.38% and [[Ruthenian language|Ruthenian]] (or [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]) with 5.46%. 20 years later, when the city switched to royal Romanian administration, the [[Demographic history of Romania#29 December 1930 census|1930 census]] recorded a population which amounted to {{circa}} 17,000 inhabitants with the following ethno-linguistic composition:<ref>{{cite web| url=https://archive.org/stream/recensamntulgene02inst#page/434/mode/2up| title=Recens\u0103m\u00e2nul general al popula\u021biei Rom\u00e2niei din 29 decemvrie 1930}}</ref>\n\n* [[Romanians]]: 60.2%\n* [[Germans of Romania|Germans]] <small>(i.e. [[Bukovina Germans]])</small>: 16.7%\n* [[History of the Jews in Romania|Jews]]: 15.4%\n* [[Ukrainians of Romania|Ukrainians]]: 3.7%\n* [[Poles in Romania|Poles]]: 2.0%\n\nAccording to the [[Demographic history of Romania#20 October 2011 census|2011 census]] data, Suceava had a population of 92,121,<ref name=\"INSSER\">{{cite web | url = http://www.suceava.insse.ro/phpfiles/Comunicat%20-%20pt%20site-DATE%20PROVIZORII%20RPL%202011%202_Suceava.pdf | title = 2011 Census | date = February 2, 2012 | access-date = March 12, 2012 | publisher = [[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|INSSE]] | language = Romanian | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130604040638/http://www.suceava.insse.ro/phpfiles/Comunicat%20-%20pt%20site-DATE%20PROVIZORII%20RPL%202011%202_Suceava.pdf | archive-date = June 4, 2013 | df =  }}</ref> a decrease from the figure recorded at the 2002 census (106,138), making it the 23rd [[List of cities and towns in Romania|largest city]] in Romania at that time. Additionally, the ethnic composition was as follows:\n\n* [[Romanians]]: 98.3%\n* [[Romani people|Roma]]: 0.7%\n* [[Ukrainians in Romania|Ukrainians]]: 0.3%\n* [[Germans of Romania|Germans]] <small>(i.e. [[Bukovina Germans]])</small>: 0.2%\n* [[Poles in Romania|Poles]]: 0.1%\n* [[Lipovans]]: 0.1%\n* Other ethnic groups: 0.3%\n\n== Administration and local politics ==\n\n=== List of mayors (1990\u2013present) ===\n\n[[File:Franz Des Loges.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Former [[Austria]]n-born mayor [[:ro:Franz Des Loges|Franz Des Loges]] (of [[Swiss people|Swiss-French]] origin) is credited with modernising the city as well as developing its culture and infrastructure during his term (1891\u20131914).<ref>{{cite web|title=Primarul austriac care a adus energia electric\u0103, iluminatul public, alimentarea cu ap\u0103, canalizarea \u015fi str\u0103zile asfaltate \u00een Suceava|work=Ziarul Adev\u0103rul|author=www.adevarul.ro|url=https://adevarul.ro/locale/suceava/primarul-austriac-adus-energia-electricailuminatul-public-alimentarea-apa-canalizarea-strazile-asfaltate-insuceava-1_54c9de4b448e03c0fd103ef9/index.html|date=29 January 2015|accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>]]\n\nThe mayors who have administered the city since Romania's transition back to [[democracy]] and a free [[market economy]] in the wake of the [[Romanian Revolution|1989 revolution]] have been the following ones:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=1 | N\u00ba\n! colspan=1 | Name\n! colspan=1 | Term start\n! colspan=1 | Term end\n! colspan=1 | Political party\n|-bgcolor={{Independent/meta/color}}\n! 1\n| Filaret Poenariu\n| 1990\n| 1992\n| [[Independent politician|Independent]]\n|-bgcolor={{Ecologist Party of Romania/meta/color}}\n! 2\n| Gheorghe Toma\n| 1992\n| 1996\n| [[Ecologist Party of Romania]] (PER)\n|-bgcolor={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}\n! 3\n| [[:ro:Constantin Sofroni|Constantin Sofroni]]\n| 1996\n| 2000\n| [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party]] (PNL)<sup>1</sup>\n|-bgcolor={{Social Democratic Party (Romania)/meta/color}}\n! 4\n| Marian Ionescu\n| 2000\n| 2004\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party]] (PSD)\n|-bgcolor={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}\n! 5\n| [[:ro:Ion Lungu|Ion Lungu]]\n| 2004\n| present\n| [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party]] (PNL)<sup>2</sup>\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Notes''':\n\n<sup>1</sup> <small>Initially elected on the lists of the [[Democratic Agrarian Party of Romania]] (PDAR) but subsequently switched to the National Liberal Party (PNL).</small><ref>{{cite web|title=Fostul primar Constantin Sofroni, cet\u0103\u021bean de onoare post-mortem|work=Crai Nou|author=www.crainou.ro|url=https://www.crainou.ro/2005/03/18/fostul-primar-constantin-sofroni-cetatean-de-onoare-post-mortem/|date=18 March 2005|accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n<br>\n<sup>2</sup> <small>Initially elected on the lists of the [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party]] (PNL), subsequently switched to the [[Democratic Liberal Party (Romania)|Democratic Liberal Party]], then re-elected on the lists of the PNL</small>\n\n=== City council ===\n\n[[File:Primaria municipiului Suceava2.jpg|thumb|right|Suceava City Hall]]\n\nThe city's current local council has the following multi-party political composition, based on the results of the ballots cast at the [[2016 Romanian local elections]]:\n\n{| cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Party\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Seats\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" colspan=\"10\" | Current Council\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party (PNL)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''10'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp; \n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party (PSD)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''8'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (Romania)|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (ALDE)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''3'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| [[People's Movement Party|People's Movement Party (PMP)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|}\n\n==Culture==\n\n===The Seat Fortress of Suceava===\n\n[[File:Cetatea de Scaun a Sucevei13.jpg|thumb|right|The access bridge and circular bastion of the seat fortress.]]\n\nSuceava is the place of several medieval sites that are closely linked with the history of the former [[Moldavia|Principality of Moldavia]]. By far the most significant (and at the same time the most well preserved one) is the Seat Fortress of Suceava ({{lang-ro|Cetatea de Scaun a Sucevei}}) or Suceava Citadel, a medieval castle situated on the eastern edge of the contemporary city.\n\nThe fortress was built during the reign of [[Petru II of Moldavia|Petru of Moldavia]] (1375\u20131391), also known as Petru Mu\u0219at. It was further expanded and strengthened during the reigns of [[Alexander I of Moldavia]] (1400\u20131432) and [[Stephen III of Moldavia|Stephen the Great]] (1457\u20131504). The medieval castle was part of the fortification system built in [[Moldavia]] in the late 14th century, because of the emergence of the Ottoman danger. It became strong enough to hold off an attack by Ottoman sultan [[Mehmed II]] (the conqueror of [[Constantinople]]), in 1476.\n\nSuceava was the capital city of the former Principality of Moldavia between 1388 and 1565. During this period, the castle served as princely residence. [[Alexandru L\u0103pu\u0219neanu]] had subsequently moved the Moldavian capital to [[Ia\u0219i]] in 1565, so the castle lost its status. Afterwards, the citadel entered a period of steep decline. In 1675, during the reign of voivode Dumitra\u0219cu Cantacuzino, the fortress was destroyed. Then, for over two centuries, the castle was completely deserted.\n\n[[File:Cetatea de Scaun a Sucevei la ceas de seara.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The late 14th century Moldavian seat fortress as seen during nighttime in May, 2015.]]\n\nIn late 19th century and early 20th century, under the patronage of Austrian architect [[:ro:Karl Romstorfer|Karl Adolf Romstorfer]], a series of rehabilitation works and archaeological research were conducted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dragusanul.ro/romstorfer-vienezul-care-a-indatorat-bucovina/|author=Dragu\u0219anul.ro|work=Dr\u0103gu\u0219anul|title=Romstorfer, vienezul care a \u00eendatorat Bucovina (in Romanian)|accessdate= 8 March 2020}}</ref> Between 1961 and 1970 other restoration and consolidation works were carried out. In 2013, a major reconstruction program was launched, to return the castle to its original architecture and shape.\n\nThe Seat Fortress of Suceava consists of two concentric citadels. The inner citadel, known as ''fortul mu\u0219atin'', has a rectangular shape and a patio. It was built by Petru Mu\u0219at in late 14th century. In the second half of the 15th century, Stephen the Great expanded the structure, by adding another citadel that has a circular shape which surrounds the old one.\n\nAfter 1476, new fortifications were added to the outer citadel. Furthermore, the whole castle is encircled by a large defensive ditch. Today, the fortress is a landmark of Suceava and a noteworthy touristic attraction. Since 2011, it has also been used for hosting cultural events such as the [[rock music]] festival Bucovina Rock Castle. The festival had attracted a series of noteworthy national and international musical acts (e.g. guitarist [[Jan Akkerman]], formerly of Dutch [[progressive rock]] band [[Focus (band)|Focus]]).<ref>[http://www.bucovinarockcastle.ro Bucovina Rock Castle official website (in Romanian)]</ref>\n\n===The Princely Court of Suceava===\n\n[[File:Curtea domneasca din Suceava9.jpg|thumb|left|Present-day ruins of the local Princely Court.]]\n\nThe Princely Court of Suceava ({{lang-ro|Curtea Domneasc\u0103 din Suceava}}) was built and developed related with the Seat Fortress. In late 14th century, voivode Petru Mu\u0219at built the Princely House, a structure made in wood, which included a cellar. After 1400, Alexander I of Moldavia rebuilt the wooden house and added a surrounding wall made of stone and a complex of buildings, also made of stone. In the second half of the 15th century, the Princely Court was severely affected by fire, the wooden house being completely burned out.\n\nDuring his reign, Stephen the Great (1457\u20131504) restored the whole complex. A new Princely House was built, this time made of stone, and the other buildings were extended. [[Vasile Lupu]] (1634\u20131653) was the last ruler of Moldavia who took care of the Princely Court. During his time, the cellars were rehabilitated. The complex was abandoned in late 17th century, the buildings and the walls being gradually dismantled. Currently, on the site of the Princely Court there are only ruins and leftovers of the former buildings.\n\nThe ruins of the former medieval court are located in the city center of Suceava. In the 14th\u201317th centuries, in the proximity of the Princely Court there were built several churches that still exist today and attract tourists.\n\n[[File:Cetatea \u015echeia10.jpg|thumb|right|The ruined walls of the \u0218cheia Fortress on \u0218eptilici Hill.]]\n\n===\u0218cheia Fortress===\n\nOn the north-western edge of the contemporary city, on a hilltop, there is another medieval citadel known as ''\u0218cheia'' Fortress ({{lang-ro|Cetatea \u0218cheia}}) or the Western Fortress of Suceava ({{lang-ro|Cetatea de Apus a Sucevei}}). Unlike the Seat Fortress, ''\u0218cheia'' Fortress has left nothing but some ruined walls. The citadel proper was built during the reign of Petru Mu\u0219at during the late 14th century, but was short-lived, given that it was dismantled during the early 15th century, in the time of [[Alexander I of Moldavia]]. ''\u0218cheia'' Fortress, just like the main Seat Fortress, was part of the fortification system built in medieval Principality of Moldavia during the late 14th century.\n\n===Museums===\n\n[[File:Muzeul Judetean din Suceava7.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The entrance to the Bukovina History Museum. During the [[interwar period]], the building served as Suceava County prefecture.]]\n\nThe first museum in Suceava was opened in 1900, by the initiative of some local intellectuals. In the beginning, the museum included only a few collections that were obtained as a result of the researches and excavation works at the Seat Fortress of Suceava. The museum was expanded and developed over time and became an important cultural institution, currently named [[Bukovina Museum]] ({{lang-ro|Muzeul Bucovinei}}). It has several departments and administers the medieval sites of the Seat Fortress, ''\u0218cheia'' Fortress and the Princely Court, local museums (Bukovina Village Museum, the history, ethnographic, and natural sciences museums), the memorial houses of [[Simion Florea Marian]] in Suceava, [[Nicolae Labi\u0219]] in [[M\u0103lini]], [[:ro:Eusebiu Camilar|Eusebiu Camilar]] in [[Ude\u0219ti]], [[Ciprian Porumbescu]] in [[Ciprian Porumbescu, Suceava|Stupca]], and two traditional houses located in [[Solca]] and [[Bilca]].\n\nThe oldest department of Bukovina Museum is the history museum, which was the backbone for creating a county museum at Suceava. This museum presents the local history of Suceava and Moldavia in the context of Romanian national history. The exhibits of the history museum and the offices of Bukovina Museum are located in a historic building, in the city center. The building, which hosted the prefecture of Suceava County during the interwar period, was built between 1902\u20131903. Since 1968, it houses the history museum. In 2014, the building and the museum entered an extensive program of modernization, rehabilitation, and expansion.\n\n{{multiple image|perrow=2|total_width=300|align=left\n|image1 = Cr\u00e2\u0219ma din \u0218aru Dornei - panoramio.jpg|caption1=Inn from [[Vatra Dornei|Dorna]] ({{lang-de|Dorna Watra}}) ethnographic area, exhibited at Bukovina Village Museum\n|image2 = Casa Vicovu de Jos1.jpg|caption2=Traditional household from [[Vicovu de Jos]] ({{lang-de|Unter Wikow}})\n|image3 = Gospod\u0103ria Straja6.jpg|caption3=Traditional household from [[Straja, Suceava|Straja]] ({{lang-de|Strasza}})\n|image4 = Moara din M\u0103n\u0103stirea Humorului.jpg|caption4=Windmill from [[M\u0103n\u0103stirea Humorului]] ({{lang-de|Humora Kloster}})\n}}\n\nAt the history museum there is a reconstitution of a scene from the former throne hall located in the Seat Fortress. The scene presents some notable people from the history of Moldavia, made in glass fiber: [[Stephen III of Moldavia|Stephen the Great]] (ruler of Moldavia), Maria Voichi\u021ba (his third wife), [[Bogdan III the One-Eyed]] (his son and successor to the throne), officials of that time. The scene chosen to be reconstructed is an allotment of land for peasants. The reconstitution is based on medieval documents, frescoes and archaeological researches. Furthermore, the history museum periodically organizes a wide range of cultural events, several of which also involve the local branch of the [[Democratic Forum of Germans in Romania]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.istorielocala.ro/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=878:forumul-democrat-al-germanilor-din-bucovina&Itemid=204|author=www.istorielocala.ro|work=Istoria Local\u0103 @ biblioteca ta public\u0103|title=Forumul Democrat al Germanilor din Bucovina (in Romanian)|date= 14 October 2013| accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adz.ro/artikel/artikel/die-geschichte-der-deutschen-in-rumaenien-wurde-noch-nicht-zu-ende-geschrieben/|author=www.adz.ro|work=Allgemeine Deutsche Zeitung f\u00fcr Rum\u00e4nien|title=Die Geschichte der Deutschen in Rum\u00e4nien wurde noch nicht zu Ende geschrieben (in German)|date= 8 January 2014| accessdate= 1 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nBukovina Village Museum ({{lang-ro|Muzeul Satului Bucovinean}}) is an open-air museum that highlights the traditional cultural and architectural heritage of [[Bukovina]] region. It is located in the eastern part of Suceava, near the Seat Fortress. It was founded in the 1970s, but its major expansion and development took place after 1990. The museum is designed as a traditional village in Bukovina, containing houses and various objectives from the ethnographic areas of [[R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]], [[Gura Humorului|Humor]], [[C\u00e2mpulung Moldovenesc]], [[Vatra Dornei|Dorna]], and [[F\u0103lticeni]].\n\nThe museum includes among others a water mill from [[M\u0103n\u0103stirea Humorului]], a traditional blacksmith workshop, a pottery workshop from [[Marginea]] and one of the many old wooden churches in northern Moldavia: Church of the Ascension, a Romanian Orthodox wooden church built in 1783 in [[Vama, Suceava|Vama]], a village in [[Suceava County]]. The bell tower is also made in wood, and dates from 1787. The church and the bell tower were both relocated in 2001, and currently are part of the museum.\n\n[[File:Hanul Domnesc din Suceava9.jpg|thumb|right|Entrance to the Princely Inn (now Ethnographic Museum)]]\n\nBesides Bukovina Village Museum, another museum that reflects the traditional life in this part of Romania is the ethnographic museum. It was opened in 1968 and includes old collections and exhibits that are housed in a medieval inn located in the center of Suceava, known as the Princely Inn of Suceava ({{lang-ro|Hanul Domnesc din Suceava}}). This landmark dates from the late 16th and early 17th century. It was built of stone and has two floors and a cellar. During the Austrian rule (1775\u20131918), the inn operated as a hunting lodge for the imperial family. Since 1968, it hosts the ethnographic museum. The Princely Inn is the oldest civic building in Suceava which had not been seriously affected by time and maintained its original architecture.\n\n[[File:Muzeul de Stiintele Naturii din Suceava4.jpg|thumb|right|Natural Sciences Museum]]\n\nThe natural sciences museum was founded in 1976\u20131977, being the newest museum in Suceava. It highlights the flora and fauna of the surrounding area. The museum's rare exhibits and collections are housed in an old building, located in the central park of the city and built between 1811\u20131814. In the past, before being an attraction for visitors, the building operated as a school for boys.\n\nAlong with all these museums, Bukovina Museum includes memorial houses of some writers and artists born in this area of the country. The memorial house of Simion Florea Marian ({{lang-ro|Casa memorial\u0103 Simion Florea Marian}}) is the only one located in Suceava, the other ones being in the surrounding area. The memorial house operates as a museum. It was opened in 1974 in the home where Romanian priest and writer Simion Florea Marian lived, from 1884 until 1907, when he died. The museum hosts a collection that contains over 10,000 volumes, over 450 collections of magazines and newspapers, of which 150 are from [[Bukovina]], manuscripts, letters, cultural and historical documents, old photos. In front of the memorial house it was opened a small park with a statue dedicated to Simion Florea Marian.\n\n===Historical buildings===\n\n[[File:Casa Aleea Trandafirilor nr. 4 din Suceava1.jpg|thumb|left|Austrian-style house situated in the old city centre.]]\n\n''Colegiul de Art\u0103 Ciprian Porumbescu'' ({{lang-ro|Ciprian Porumbescu Art College}}) is a high school which is hosted in a historic building, built in 1859, in the city center of Suceava. The building had several destinations in the past: Suceava Town Hall (until 1904) and ''\u0218coala primar\u0103 rom\u00e2n\u0103 de fete'' (Primary Romanian school for girls). Romanian jazz singer [[Anca Parghel]] taught music for a living in Suceava at this local Arts high school before turning to a professional singing career in 1989.\n\n[[File:Gara Suceava Nord.jpg|right|thumb|I\u021bcani ({{lang-de|Itzkany}}) railway station during the early 20th century.]]\n[[File:Suceava railway station (39856700481).jpg|thumb|right|Burdujeni railway station during the early 20th century.]]\n\n''Gara Suceava Nord-I\u021bcani'' ([[Suceava North railway station]], also known as ''I\u021bcani'') is a train station built in 1871 in the village of [[I\u021bcani]] (today district of Suceava). Between 1871\u20131918, it was a train station at the Austro-Hungarian border. The historic building of I\u021bcani railway station was built in the Gothic style of the Central European railway stations of that period.\n\n''Palatul de Justi\u021bie'' (The Palace of Justice) is a historic building which was built in 1885 to serve as the seat of Suceava Tribunal and Court. The building has four sides and a patio, and was designed by Viennese architect [[Fellner & Helmer|Ferdinand Fellner]]. Later, during the communist regime, the city hall was moved in this palace and operated here until 2000.\n\n''Spitalul Vechi'' (The Old Hospital) is a complex of buildings built between 1891\u20131903 which originally hosted the district hospital. The hospital ensemble consists of four pavilions of historic value and was built in the southwestern end of Suceava, in Areni neighborhood. In 1964 a new hospital building (known as ''Spitalul Nou'') was inaugurated nearby.\n\n''Colegiul Na\u021bional \u0218tefan cel Mare'' (\u0218tefan cel Mare National College) is the oldest and most prestigious high school in [[Suceava County]], established in 1860. The baroque style building which houses the high school was built between 1893\u20131895, downtown Suceava, and today is considered a historical monument.\n\n[[File:Palatul Administrativ din Suceava19.jpg|thumb|left|The Administrative Palace during the interwar period]]\n[[File:BRC Sv.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.9|St. John of Nepomuk Roman Catholic church in 1990]]\n\n''Gara Suceava-Burdujeni'' ([[Suceava railway station]], also known as ''Burdujeni'') is a train station built between 1892\u20131902 in the village of Burdujeni (today district of Suceava). Between 1902\u20131918, it was a train station at the Austro-Hungarian border. The historic building of Burdujeni railway station was built in the architectural style of [[Fribourg]] railway station, located in [[Switzerland]].\n\n[[File:Biblioteca Bucovinei I.G. Sbiera din Suceava1.jpg|thumb|right|I.G. Sbiera Bukovina Library]]\n[[File:Directia Silvica Judeteana din Suceava1.jpg|thumb|right|The County Forestry Department in Suceava]]\n[[File:Primaria din Burdujeni.jpg|thumb|right|Former Burdujeni town hall building]]\n\n''Palatul Administrativ'' (The Administrative Palace) is a historic building which was built between 1903\u20131904 to serve as the seat of Suceava City Hall. The building originally had only two sides of the four current sides, and was designed by Viennese architect [[Peter Paul Brang]]. It was designed in the baroque style. Currently, the palace houses the prefecture and the county council of Suceava County.\n\n[[File:Casa_Polon\u0103_din_Suceava4.jpg|thumb|left|The 'Dom Polski' Polish House]]\n\n''Casa Polon\u0103'' (The Polish House) is a building made between 1903\u20131907 by the Polish community in the city of Suceava. The building was designed by architect [[Alojz Friedel]]. During the communist regime, The Polish House was nationalized, and since 1954, it housed ''Ansamblul Artistic Ciprian Porumbescu'' (Ciprian Porumbescu Artistic Ensemble). In 1984 the building was restored, and then hosted a local theatre, until 1990. In 1996, the building was returned to the Polish community of the city.\n\n''Uzina de Ap\u0103'' (The Water Plant) is a set of industrial heritage buildings, designed in 1908 by engineer G. Thiem from [[Leipzig]] and built between 1910\u20131912.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://miesarch.com/work/1112|title=Water Plant, Center for Architecture, Urban Culture and landscape|author=www.miesarch.com|work=Fundaci\u00f3 Mies van der Rohe. 2018|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref> The water plant operated in these buildings between 1912\u20131960, and then it was moved into a modern building. In 2012, in celebration of 100 years since its establishment, in the former water plant buildings there was inaugurated the Centre for Architecture, Urban Culture and Landscape in Suceava.\n\n''Biblioteca Bucovinei I.G. Sbiera'' (I.G. Sbiera Bukovina Library) is the first public library in Suceava, inaugurated on 12 December 1923. It is also the largest library in Suceava County, with over 350,000 bibliographic units. Currently, the library is hosted by two historic buildings located in downtown Suceava and built between 1925\u20131926, respectively 1929\u20131930.\n\n''The County Forestry Department'' in Suceava is an institution which operates in a heritage building located in Areni neighborhood, in the city of Suceava. The building dates from the first half of the 20th century.\n\n''The Unions House'' in Suceava is a heritage building, located in downtown Suceava, which houses the unions offices, along with some shops. The building is also known as Samuil Isopescu House.\n\n''Casa Costin Tarangul'' (Costin Tarangul House) is a heritage house dating from the 19th century (1886). The building is located next to Simion Florea Marian Memorial House, in the center of Suceava.\n\n''Casa Ciprian Porumbescu'' (Ciprian Porumbescu House) is a heritage house dating from the 19th century, where Romanian composer [[Ciprian Porumbescu]] lived and created some of his works. The house is located in Prunului street, downtown Suceava.\n\n''School No. 5 Jean Bart'' in Burdujeni (Suceava) is a school built in 1902 in the village Burdujeni, today a town district of Suceava. The building that houses the school has historic value.\n\n''School No. 6 in Burdujeni-Sat'' (Suceava) is a school built in 1911 in the village Burdujeni, today a town district of Suceava. The building that houses the school has historic value.\n\n''Former Burdujeni Town Hall'' in Suceava is a building that was built in 1902 in the village Burdujeni and initially was the town hall of the locality. In 1926 Burdujeni became a district of Suceava, and so the town hall was abolished. The historic building currently houses the headquarters of Electrica company.\n\n====I\u021bcani neighbourhood====\n\n{{multiple image|perrow = 2|total_width=300\n| image1 = Gara Suceava Nord1.jpg\n| image2 = Poli\u0163ia din I\u0163cani1.jpg\n| image3 = \u0218coala din I\u021bcani1.jpg\n| image4 = Cl\u0103dire din I\u021bcani.jpg\n| footer = Clockwise from left to right: Suceava North railway station, former police station, the old elementary school in I\u021bcani, and a local Austrian-style household.\n}}\n\n[[I\u021bcani]] ({{lang-de|Itzkany}}) is a neighbourhood located several miles northwest of the city centre. Initially established as a small village in the 15th century under the rulership of [[Alex\u0103ndrel of Moldavia]], it subsequently expanded as a German-speaking colony much later, specifically starting in the late 19th century, seeing an influx of German settlers during the [[Josephine colonization]] ({{lang-de|Josephinische Kolonisation}}) which took place in the time of the [[Austrian Empire]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bukovinasociety.org/buko/sitefiles/Talsky-Josef-Heimat-von-gestern-Regional-distribution-of-Germans-in-Bukovina.html|author=www.bukovinasociety.org|work=The Bukovina Society of the Americas|title=The Regional Distribution of the Germans in Bukovina|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bukovinasociety.org/buko/sitefiles/Stephani-Claus-1978-Settlement-of-German-Population-Groups-in-Bukovina-E.html|author=www.bukovinasociety.org|work=The Bukovina Society of the Americas|title=The Golden Bistritz - The Settlement of German Population Groups in Bukovina|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref> [[Suceava North railway station|The north railway station]] (which depicts architectural elements of both [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic revival]] and [[Neo-romanticism|Neo-romanticist]] styles, also the oldest in the city) is situated in this neighbourhood as well.\n\n=== Monuments ===\n\nNear the fortress, in \u0218ipote-Cetate Park, there is an [[equestrian statue]] of Stephen the Great, designed and made by the local sculptor Iftimie B\u00e2rleanu in 1977. The monument has 23 meters in height, being the tallest equestrian statue in Romania. In the city centre there's also a statue dedicated to [[Petru Mu\u0219at]], Prince of Moldavia between 1375\u20131391.\n\n===Religious buildings===\n\n====Romanian Orthodox churches====\n\nOne of the most important cultural sites in Suceava is [[Saint John the New Monastery]] which includes the monumental Church of [[Saint George]], built between 1514 and 1522. The construction began during the reign of voivode [[Bogdan III the One-Eyed]] of Moldavia, after the nearby Mir\u0103u\u021bi Church (the metropolitan cathedral of Moldavia at that moment) was devastated in 1513. The construction was completed by [[Stephen IV of Moldavia]] (also known as \u0218tef\u0103ni\u021b\u0103). The monastery church served as metropolitan cathedral of Moldavia until 1677. It has frescoes painted on the outside, typical of the region, and is one of eight buildings that make up the [[churches of Moldavia]] [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]].<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/598 Churches of Moldavia] at the UNESCO site</ref> Since 1991 Saint John the New Monastery serves as the cathedral of the [[Archdiocese of Suceava and R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]]. Saint John the New<ref>[http://sfantulioancelnou.8k.ro/ sfantulioancelnou.8k.ro] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091227211255/http://sfantulioancelnou.8k.ro/ |date=2009-12-27 }}</ref> was a Moldavian monk who preached during Turkish occupation and was subsequently martyred in Cetatea Alb\u0103, present-day [[Bilhorod-Dnistrovskyi]] in [[Ukraine]]. [[Alexander I of Moldavia]] brought his relics to Suceava in 1402.\n\nMir\u0103u\u021bi Church, dedicated to Saint George, is the oldest religious building in Suceava, founded by [[Petru II of Moldavia]] in late 14th century, in the same period with the Seat Fortress, when he moved the capital from [[Siret]] to Suceava. The church established the city as a see of it. Mir\u0103u\u021bi was the metropolitan cathedral of Moldavia between 1402 and 1522, when the church of Saint John the New Monastery was completed. In 1402, the relics of Saint John the New were transferred to this church from [[Cetatea Alb\u0103]], and then, in 1589 transferred again to the nearby monastery church by voivode [[Peter the Lame]]. The name ''Mir\u0103u\u021bi'' derives from the fact that it was the coronation church of Moldavia until 1522. [[Stephen the Great]] was crowned in here in 1457. After the church was devastated, it was rebuilt in early 17th century, and then, in the 18th century, abandoned.\n\nChurch of [[Saint Demetrius of Thessaloniki|Saint Demetrius]] was founded by [[Peter IV Rare\u0219]], ruler of Moldavia (1527\u20131538, 1541\u20131546), and the son of Stephan the Great. The church was built in 1534\u20131535, with a bell tower added in 1560\u20131561 by Alexandru L\u0103pu\u0219neanu. The bell tower is 40 meters high, being the tallest bell tower in Suceava and a landmark of the city. The church had frescoes painted on the outside, that are still visible on one side wall. The frescoes inside were restored recently. Church of Saint Demetrius is located near the ruins of the former Princely Court of Suceava.\n\n{{multiple image|perrow = 2|total_width=300\n| image1 = M\u0103n\u0103stirea Sf\u00e2ntul Ioan cel Nou35.jpg\n| image2 = Biserica Sf. Dumitru din Suceava34.jpg\n| image3 = Biserica Mirauti27.jpg\n| image4 = Biserica Sf\u00e2ntul Nicolae din Suceava2.jpg\n| footer = Clockwise from left to right: St. John the New Monastery (UNESCO World Heritage site), Church of St. Demetrius, Mir\u0103u\u021bi Church, Church of St. Nicholas.\n}}\n\nFurthermore, there is another old church near these ruins. Church of [[Saint John the Baptist]], also known as Coconilor Church or Domni\u021belor Church, was founded in 1643 by [[Vasile Lupu]], voivode of Moldavia between 1632 and 1653. It has no exterior frescoes and a short bell tower that has its roof linked with the roof above the church. In its early days, the church functioned as a chapel for the Princely Court.\n\nChurch of the Resurrection (located in the proximity of Saint John the New Monastery) dates from 1551, and was founded by Elena Rare\u0219, the wife of voivode Peter IV Rare\u0219. The church has no tower above the [[cella|naos]], its architecture reflecting the urban style of the medieval period. Instead of the bell tower, the church has a [[zvonnitsa]], an architectural form especially used in the [[Russian architecture]] of the 14th\u201317th centuries. Church of the Resurrection was used by the local Roman Catholic community during the Habsburg occupation, and then by the Ruthenian Greek Catholic community, until 1936. It is also known as ''V\u0103scresenia Church'' or ''Elena Doamna'' Church.\n\nChurch of [[Saint Nicholas]] (Pr\u0103jescu) is another religious building in Suceava that features the medieval Moldavian architectural style. The present church was rebuilt by treasurer Nicoar\u0103 Pr\u0103jescu in 1611, during the reign of Constantin Movil\u0103 (1607\u20131611). Throughout its history, the church functioned as a necropolis for the local [[boyar]]s.\n\nBetween the city center and I\u021bcani neighborhood, on the slopes that descend to the [[Suceava (river)|Suceava river valley]], there is Church of the Assumption, another old Romanian Orthodox church, founded in the first half of the 17th century (1639). The church was built on the place where I\u021bcani Monastery existed before. It functioned as a nunnery until late 18th century. Today it is parish church, and has a zvonnitsa similar to that of Church of the Resurrection, located downtown.\n\nIn Burdujeni neighborhood, {{convert|4|km|0|abbr=on}} north-east of the city center, there is Teodoreni Monastery, founded in 1597 by local boyar Teodor Movil\u0103, the elder brother of [[Ieremia Movil\u0103]], ruler of Moldavia (1595\u20131600, 1600\u20131606). Burdujeni village (now a district of Suceava) was established and developed around this monastery. The set of buildings includes Church of Ascension, the bell tower, living quarters for nuns and a surrounding wall. Just {{convert|1|km|1|abbr=on}} north of Teodoreni Monastery, in the old district of Burdujeni, there is Church of the Holy Trinity, founded by archimandrite Filaret Scriban in 1851.\n\nI\u021bcani neighborhood has two Romanian Orthodox churches founded in the first half of the 20th century: Church of the Holy Archangels (built near [[Suceava North railway station]], in 1933\u20131938) and Church of the Holy Apostles (located on [[European route E85]] and built in 1905\u20131908 by the German community of I\u021bcani, initially as a Lutheran church).\n\n[[Church of the Holy Cross, P\u0103tr\u0103u\u021bi|Church of the Holy Cross]], located in [[P\u0103tr\u0103u\u021bi]] village (a few miles north-west of I\u021bcani), was founded in 1487 by Stephen the Great, and is one of the monuments that make up the [[churches of Moldavia]] [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]]. Also not far away from I\u021bcani, there is [[Dragomirna Monastery]], established by clergyman [[Anastasie Crimca]] in 1609. [[Vorone\u021b Monastery]] is located {{convert|40|km|0|abbr=on}} west of Suceava, in the town of [[Gura Humorului]].\n\n====German Roman Catholic and Lutheran churches====\n\n{{multiple image|perrow = 2|total_width=200\n| image1 = Biserica Sf. Ioan Nepomuk din Suceava44.jpg\n| image2 = Biserica Sf. Elisabeta din Itcani15.jpg\n| image3 = Biserica Sf. Apostoli din Itcani10.jpg\n| image4 = Biserica Evanghelic\u0103 din Suceava1.jpg\n| footer = Clockwise from left to right: St. John of Nepomuk Roman Catholic Church, St. Elizabeth Roman Catholic Church,  St. Apostles Lutheran Church, The Evangelical Church.\n}}\n\nDuring the late [[Modern Age]] until the mid 20th century, a sizable [[Bukovina Germans|German]] community lived in Suceava, making up almost a quarter of the total population of the city in the 1900s. They were of both Roman Catholic and Evangelical Lutheran faith given the fact that they had a rather diverse geographic origin from which they initially stemmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bukowinafreunde.de/Neuer%20Ordner/faq/Bukovina%20and%20its%20Bukovina%20Germans.pdf|author=www.bukowinafreunde.de|work=Bukowina Freunde|title=Bukovina and its Bukovina Germans by Willi Kosiul|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://master.cedcsv.ro/cedc/infos/informatica/Minoritatile_conlocuitoare_din_judetul_Suceava/Germanii/germanii.html|author=www.mastercedcsv.ro|work=Minorit\u0103\u021bile conlocuitoare din jude\u021bul Suceava|title=Germanii (in Romanian)|accessdate= 31 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTherefore, these German-speaking colonists who were settled by the Austrian Empire in the city proper can trace their origins most notably from present-day southern [[Germany]], [[Austria]], and [[Bohemia]], both Catholics and Protestants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bukovinasociety.org/buko/sitefiles/Welisch-2002-1.html|author=www.bukovinasociety.org|work=The Bukovina Society of the Americas|title=The History of Bukovina by Dr. Sophie A. Welisch|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref> Several religious buildings that served both aforementioned religious denominations can still be found today both in the city proper and in the [[I\u021bcani]] neighborhood, where a bygone numerous German-speaking community (stemming from contemporary [[Rhineland-Palatinate]] land in [[Germany]]) once lived.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.monitorulsv.ro/Local/2009-08-24/Viata-germanilor-bucovineni-din-Itcanii-Noi|author=www.monitorulsv.ro|work=Monitorul de Suceava|title=Via\u0163a germanilor bucovineni din I\u0163canii Noi|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Armenian Orthodox churches====\n\n[[File:Biserica Sf. Cruce din Suceava.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Church of the Holy Cross]]\n[[File:M\u0103n\u0103stirea Zamca30.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Zamca Monastery]]\n\nIn the past, Suceava used to have an important Armenian community as well. Their cultural and historical legacy is highlighted by a series of well preserved religious buildings that still exist to this today.\n\nThe most representative ecclesiastical landmark established by the local Armenian population is Zamca Monastery (the term Zamca can actually trace its linguistic origin to [[Polish language|Polish]], denoting as such a 'fortified place' and being named this way by [[List of Polish monarchs|King]] [[John III Sobieski|Jan Sobieski]] of [[Crown of the Kingdom of Poland|Poland]] in 1691), a fortified complex of buildings located on a plateau at the western point of the contemporary city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://calatoresc.ro/descopera-orasul-suceava/|author=Isabela|work=c\u0103l\u0103toresc.ro|title=Descoper\u0103 ora\u0219ul Suceava (in Romanian)|date=2 October 2013|accessdate= 28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nZamca Monastery was constructed between 1551 and 1606 and its church is dedicated to Saint Auxentius. Along with the church, the monastery includes several buildings made of stone and a defensive wall that surrounds the whole medieval complex.\n\nBetween Zamca Monastery and the city center there are two more Armenian Orthodox churches. Church of Saint Simon (also known as The Red Tower Church because of its bell tower) was founded in 1513. The bell tower was constructed in 1551.\n\nThe church has an old Armenian cemetery in the proximity and a chapel that was built in 1902 (Pruncul Chapel). Church of the Holy Cross was established in 1521 and was renovated several times in its history. The Armenian parsonage is located near the church, along with several old tomb stones.\n\nHagigadar Monastery is another medieval complex built by the local Armenians. It was founded in 1512\u20131513, and is located on the south-western proximity of the city, on a valley near [[European route E85]].\n\n==Tourism==\n\nIn the past few years Suceava started to evolve more rapidly. The most important sights in the town date from its time as a princely capital (i.e. the Middle Ages). There are numerous museums in the city proper including, most notably, the Bucovina History Museum, the Bucovina Village Museum,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://muzeulbucovinei.ro/muzeul-satului-bucovinean/|author=www.monitorulsv.ro|work=Muzeul Bucovinei|title=Muzeul Satului Bucovinean|accessdate= 16 June 2018}}</ref> Bucovina Ethnographic Museum (housed in an inn dating back to the 17th century),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orasulsuceava.ro/unde-iesim/obiective-turistice/muzee/muzeul-etnografic-hanul-domnesc/|work=Ora\u0219ul Suceava|title=Muzeul Etnografic Hanul Domnesc (in Romanian)|accessdate= 28 September 2018}}</ref> or the Natural History Museum.\n\n== Sports ==\n\n=== Football ===\n\n[[File:Stadionul Areni7.jpg|thumb|right|Areni Stadium stand]]\n\n[[ACS Foresta Suceava]] ({{lang-ro|Asocia\u021bia Club Sportiv Foresta Suceava}}), formerly known as Rapid CFR Suceava, is the football team that currently represents the city of Suceava in the third tier of the Romanian football system, more specifically in [[Liga III]].\n\nIn the past, the city has also had other significant football clubs competing in either [[Liga I]] or Liga II (depending on their level of performance) such as [[CSM Suceava]], [[FC Cetatea Suceava]], or [[Foresta F\u0103lticeni|Foresta Suceava]] (the latter one being initially based in the city of [[F\u0103lticeni]] from the same county). The city also used to have another Liga III side called [[Sporting Suceava]], but due to financing reasons the club had subsequently went bankrupt and ceased playing.\n\nAll the major sporting events are hosted on the [[Stadionul Areni|Areni Stadium]], a multi-purpose stadium in Suceava. It is currently the home ground of ACS Foresta Suceava and can hold up to 12,500 people. The stadium was initially opened in 1963 as the \"''Municipal Stadium''\".\n\n=== Handball ===\n\n[[CSU Suceava|CS Universitatea Bucovina Suceava]] is the city's men's [[handball]] team which currently competes in the [[Liga Na\u021bional\u0103 (men's handball)|Romanian Handball League]] ({{lang-ro|Liga Na\u021bional\u0103}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://csusuceava.ro/echipa/istoric/|title=Echipa - Istoric|publisher=csusuceava.ro|access-date=31 May 2011|language=Romanian|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830072422/http://csusuceava.ro/echipa/istoric/|archive-date=30 August 2013|df=}}</ref> It was founded in 2002 and it started playing in the first tier of the Romanian handball system in 2006. In 2011 it achieved its greatest performance to date, namely finishing 3rd in the national handball division.\n\n==Schooling and education==\nThe main university of the city (and also of the entire county) is the [[\u0218tefan cel Mare University of Suceava]] established in 1990, which has 10,138 students to date.\n\n[[File:Universitatea din Suceava1.jpg|thumb|\u015etefan cel Mare University of Suceava]]\nThe most prominent high schools with theoretical pathway are as follows:\n\n'''National College \"Mihai Eminescu\" Suceava'''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cn-eminescu.ro/| title=Colegiul Na\u021bional \"Mihai Eminescu\" din Suceava| accessdate= 17 June 2018}}</ref>\n*Named after the most well-known Moldavian and Romanian poet, [[Mihai Eminescu]]\n*Main study offers are: Social Sciences, Mathematics and Informatics, Philology.\n\n'''National College \"Petru Rare\u0219\" Suceava'''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cnprsv.ro/| title=Coleiul Na\u021bional \"Petru Rare\u0219\" din Suceava| accessdate= 17 June 2018}}</ref>\n*Named after the voievod of Moldavia, [[Peter IV Rare\u015f]]\n*Main study offers are: English, Philology, Mathematics and Informatics.\n\n[[File:Liceul \u0218tefan cel Mare din Suceava.jpg|thumb|\u0218tefan cel Mare National College]]\n\n'''National College \"\u0218tefan cel Mare\" Suceava'''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cnstefancelmare.ro| title=Colegiul Na\u021bional \"\u0218tefan cel Mare\" din Suceava| accessdate= 17 June 2018}}</ref>\n*Named after the prince of Moldavia between the years 1457 and 1504, [[Stephen III of Moldavia]]\n*Main study offers are: Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Informatics.\n\n'''Economical College \"Dimitre Cantemir\" Suceava'''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://master.cedcsv.ro/cedc/| title=Colegiul Economic \"Dimitrie Cantemir\" Suceava| accessdate= 17 June 2018}}</ref>\n*Named after the twice Prince of Moldavia and the famous writer of the Descriptio Moldavie, [[Dimitrie Cantemir]].\n*It is the only economics high-school in Suceava. \n*Main study offers are Tourism, Gastronomy, Alimentation, Economy, Countability and Trade.\n*The main profile which the school promovates is the Technical profile.\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Air===\n\n[[File:Aerogara Suceava.jpg|thumb|right|Suceava \u015etefan cel Mare International Airport - new TWR and main terminal building in 2015.]]\n\nSuceava is served by the [[Suceava International Airport|Suceava International \"\u015etefan cel Mare\" Airport]] (SCV), located {{convert|12|km|abbr=on}} east of the city centre, in the small town of [[Salcea]].<ref name=\"loc\">[http://www.aeroportsuceava.ro/en/2016-01-29-19-50-13/2016-01-29-19-55-57.html LRSV location] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325173110/http://aeroportsuceava.ro/en/2016-01-29-19-50-13/2016-01-29-19-55-57.html |date=2016-03-25 }}</ref> The airport initially opened in 1962 when commercial services started with [[TAROM]], the oldest operating Romanian airline.<ref name=\"history\">[http://www.aeroportsuceava.ro/en/2012-01-04-13-30-45/istoric About Suceava Airport] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151011162947/http://www.aeroportsuceava.ro/en/2012-01-04-13-30-45/istoric |date=2015-10-11 }}</ref> In 1963, the runway was paved, and an apron was built. Services by TAROM were discontinued in 2001, but resumed in 2004. During this period, the airport was served only by [[Angel Airlines (Romania)|Angel Airlines]]. In March 2005, the airport was renamed ''\u0218tefan cel Mare Airport'', and opened to international traffic.\n\nIn 2013, Suceava International Airport started a plan (worth {{c.}} \u20ac39 million) to rebuild and extend the old runway of {{convert|1800|m|abbr=on|0}}, to construct a new control tower and to install a new [[Instrument landing system|ILS system]].<ref>[http://www.aeroportsuceava.ro/documente/comunicate/9-08-2013.pdf Suceava Airport press release]</ref> In August 2013, the construction works commenced,<ref>[http://www.obiectivdesuceava.ro/local/lucrarile-la-aeroportul-sucevei-au-demarat-fara-surle-si-trambite/ Lucr\u0103rile la aeroportul Sucevei au demarat] {{in lang|ro}}</ref> and on 12 January 2014, the airport closed in order to allow the runway works to resume. The old concrete runway was completely removed, and a new runway, made out of asphalt, was constructed. \n\nOn 25 October 2015, the airport was officially reopened.<ref>[http://www.agerpres.ro/social/2015/10/25/aeroportul-suceava-deschis-traficului-aerian-intern-si-international-18-19-08 Aeroportul Suceava deschis traficului aerian intern \u0219i interna\u021bional] {{in lang|ro}}</ref> As of 2018, Suceava International Airport had an annual traffic of 353,280 passengers, a local record thus far, making it the [[List of the busiest airports in Romania|8th busiest airport in Romania]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Traficul pe Aeroportul \u201e\u0218tefan cel Mare\u201d Suceava a atins \u00een 2017 un record istoric|publisher=newsbucovina.ro|url=https://www.newsbucovina.ro/actualitate/212366/traficul-pe-aeroportul-stefan-cel-mare-suceava-atins-2017-un-record-istoric-de-261-000-de-pasageri-iar-2018-se-estimeaza-o-crestere-cu-peste-20-la-suta-prin-introducerea-de}}</ref>\n\n==Natives==\n\n{{Category see also|People from Suceava}}\n\n{{Collapsible list|title=Intellectuals and artists|\n{{Div col}}\n* [[:de:Marius Babias|Marius Babias]], art critic, author, and curator (director of [[:de:Neuer Berliner Kunstverein|Neuer Berliner Kunstverein]] since 2008)\n* [[Iosif Berman]], photographer and journalist during the [[interwar period]]\n* [[Eugeniu Botez]] (nom de plume ''Jean Bart''), writer\n* [[:ro: Stela Cheptea|Stela Cheptea]], historian and medievalist\n* [[Vladimir G\u0103itan]], actor\n* [[Norman Manea]], writer and intellectual\n* [[:ro: Ioan Neme\u0219|Ioan Neme\u0219]], physicist and biologist\n* [[:de:George Ostafi|George Ostafi]], abstract painter\n* [[Gheorghe Panaiteanu Bardasare]], painter\n* [[:ro: Nicolae Picu|Nicolae Picu]], violinist\n* [[Pamfil Polonic]], archaeologist and topographer\n* [[:ro:Ioana Rosto\u0219|Ioana Rosto\u0219]] (nom de plume ''Jane Rostos''), writer\n* [[:de:Ludwig Adolf Staufe-Simiginowicz|Ludwig Adolf Staufe-Simiginowicz]], poet and German language teacher\n{{div col end}}\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|title=Sportsmen|\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Daniel B\u0103lan]], football player and coach\n* [[Petru B\u0103lan]], rugby union footballer\n* [[Mugur Bolohan|Cristian Mugur Bolohan]], former football player and coach\n* [[Alexandru Buziuc]], football player\n* [[Ionu\u021b Dimofte]], rugby union football player\n* [[Irina Dorneanu]], Olympic rower\n* [[Iulian Dumitra\u0219]], rugby union football player\n* [[Dorin Goian]], former football player and coach\n* [[Lucian Goian]], football player\n* [[C\u0103t\u0103lin Golofca]], football player\n* [[Lidia Havri\u0219tiuc]], football player\n* [[Aleksandru Longher]], football player\n* [[Paul Mateciuc]], football player\n* [[Cosmin Pa\u0219covici]], former football player\n* [[Anca Poloco\u0219er]], handball player\n* [[Doru Popadiuc]], football player\n* [[Mihai Roman]], football player\n* [[Tiberiu Serediuc]], football player\n* [[Ovidiu Slu\u0219ariuc]], former rugby union football player\n* [[Sonia Ursu-Kim]], basketball player\n{{div col end}}\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|title=Clergymen|\n* [[Dosoftei|Dimitrie Baril\u0103]], 17th century [[Moldavia]]n [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan]], scholar, poet, and translator\n* [[Iosif Bobulescu]], 19th century bishop\n* [[Anastasie Crimca]], 16th century [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Eastern orthodox]] clergyman, calligrapher, [[Illuminated manuscript|illuminator]], and writer\n* [[Peter Mogila]], 17th century theologian\n* [[Shotzer Rebbe|Shulem Moskovitz]], [[chasidic]] [[Rebbe]]\n* [[Filaret Scriban]], 19th century theologian\n* [[Meir Shapiro]], [[Hasidic]] [[rabbi]] and [[rosh yeshiva]]\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|title=Politicians|\n* [[Luca Arbore]], 15th\u201316th century Moldavian boyar, diplomat, and statesman\n* [[Cristian Adomni\u021bei]], former PNL Minister of Education (2007\u20132008)\n* [[Eugen Bejinariu]], former PSD acting [[Prime Minister of Romania|Prime Minister]] (2004)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Founding of Moldavia|Foundation of Moldavia]]\n* [[List of rulers of Moldavia]]\n* [[Churches of Moldavia|Medieval churches of Moldavia]]\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Romania}}\n\n=== Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities ===\nSuceava is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n* {{flagicon|PRC}} [[Guizhou]], [[China]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.monitorulsv.ro/Local/2009-07-04/Sucevenii-s-au-infratit-cu-chinezii-din-Guizhou|title=Sucevenii s-au \u00eenfr\u0103\u0163it cu chinezii din Guizhou|author=www.monitorulsv.ro|date= 4 July 2009|work=Monitorul de Suceava|accessdate= 9 June 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|ISR}} [[Haifa]], [[Israel]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.monitorulsv.ro/Local/2010-04-08/Suceava-a-inceput-demersurile-de-infratire-cu-orasul-israelian-Haifa|title=Suceava a \u00eenceput demersurile de \u00eenfr\u0103\u0163ire cu ora\u015ful israelian Haifa|author=www.monitorulsv.ro|work=Monitorul de Suceava|date = 8 April 2010|accessdate= 13 June 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Laval, Mayenne|Laval]], [[France]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsme.ro/administratie/suceava-infratita-cu-orasul-francez-laval.html|title=Suceava \u00eenfr\u0103\u021bit\u0103 cu ora\u0219ul francez Laval|author=www.newsme.ro|date= 20 October 2010|work=newsMe|accessdate= 9 June 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|POL}} [[Sosnowiec]], [[Poland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primariasv.ro/portal/suceava/portal.nsf/684A6C3ACAE00E99C2257BEC0023E121/$FILE/Orasul_Sosnowiec_Polonia.pdf|title=Ora\u0219ul Sosnowiec \u2013 Polonia|author=www.primariasv.ro|work=Prim\u0103ria Municipiului Suceava|accessdate= 9 June 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|MDA}} [[Soroca]], [[Moldova|Republic of Moldova]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://radiochisinau.md/maluri-de-prut-la-630-de-ani-de-la-prima-atestare-documentara-suceava-se-infrateste-cu-soroca-doua-orasecetati-cu-legaturi-istorice-profunde---63140.html|title=Maluri de Prut: La 630 de ani de la prima atestare documentar\u0103, Suceava se \u00eenfr\u0103\u021be\u0219te cu Soroca. Dou\u0103 ora\u0219e-cet\u0103\u021bi cu leg\u0103turi istorice profunde|author=Radio Chi\u0219in\u0103u |date= 8 February 2018|work=Radio Chi\u0219in\u0103u|accessdate= 10 February 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|UKR}} [[Chernivtsi]], [[Ukraine]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primariasv.ro/portal/suceava/portal.nsf/684A6C3ACAE00E99C2257BEC0023E121/$FILE/Orasul_Cernauti_Ucraina.pdf|title=Regiunea Cern\u0103u\u0163i este situat\u0103 \u00een zona Mun\u0163ilor Carpa\u0163i din sud-vestul Ucrainei|author=www.primariasv.ro|work=Prim\u0103ria Municipiului Suceava|accessdate= 9 June 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[United States]]\n|}\n\n=== Regional, cultural, and economic partnerships ===\n\nIn addition to the official town/city twinning, the city of Suceava shares a series of regional, cultural, and economic partnerships with the following:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://primariasv.ro/portal/suceava/portal.nsf/AllByUNID/000011BE?OpenDocument|title=Prim\u0103ria Suceava - Despre ora\u0219ul Suceava (in Romanian)}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n* {{flagicon|DEU}} {{flagicon|Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg}} {{flagicon|Bayern}} [[Germany]], [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] and [[Bavaria|Bayern]] - economic, cultural, and touristic contacts with the historical region of [[Swabia]] ({{lang-de|Schwaben}})<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.romaniajournal.ro/ambassador-cord-meier-klodt-german-investors-are-looking-for-new-opportunities-in-romania/|title=Ambassador Cord Meier-Klodt: German investors are looking for new opportunities in Romania|work=The Romania Journal|author=Anca Bernovici|date=25 May 2018|accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Denmark]] - local development partnership with the city of [[Aalborg]], [[North Denmark Region|North Jutland]]\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Italy]] - local development partnership with the city of [[Naples]], [[Campania]]\n* {{flagicon|UK}} [[United Kingdom]] - local development partnership with the city of [[Liverpool]], [[North West England]]\n* {{flagicon|FRA}} [[France]] - local development partnership with the city of [[Lyon]], [[Auvergne-Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]]\n|}\n\n=== Consulates ===\n\n* {{flagicon|UKR}} [[Ukraine]] - Consulate-general\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Palatul Administrativ din Suceava18.jpg|The Administrative Palace (view of the front fa\u00e7ade)\nFile:Palatul de Finante din Suceava8.jpg|The Palace of Finance\nFile:Imagine aerian\u0103 a Palatului de Justi\u0163ie (vedere dinspre Aleea Anastasie Crimca).JPG|The Justice Palace in the city centre\nFile:Spitalul vechi din Suceava3.jpg|The Old Hospital\nFile:Gara Burdujeni.jpg|Burdujeni railway station in wintertime\nFile:Liceul de Art\u0103 din Suceava4.jpg|[[Ciprian Porumbescu]] Art College (former German-language gymnasium)\nFile:Suceava_fortress_19.jpg|Downtown Suceava, as seen from the medieval Seat Fortress (December, 2005)\nFile:View on Suceava (Romania) from Fortess.jpg|Downtown Suceava, as seen from the medieval Seat Fortress (August, 2009)\nFile:Piata 22 Decembrie din Suceava3.jpg|22 December square in downtown Suceava\nFile:Imagine aerian\u0103 a Cet\u0103\u021bii de Scaun a Sucevei.jpg|Aerial view of the Seat Fortress (June, 2015)\nFile:Suczawa twierdza.jpg|The Seat Fortress (August, 2009)\nFile:Suceava_fortress_(by_Pudelek).jpg|Panoramic view of the Seat Fortress of Suceava as seen in August, 2016\nFile:Statuia lui Petru I Mu\u0219at din Suceava2.jpg|Statue of Petru Mu\u0219at, Prince of Moldavia (between 1375\u20131391)\nFile:Suceava_-_Stauia_lui_Stefan_Cel_Mare.jpg|The equestrian statue of Stephen III of Moldavia\nFile:Hotelul Bucovina din Suceava1.jpg|Hotel Bucovina\nFile:Bloc Bd. 1 Decembrie 1918 din Suceava.jpg|Apartment blocks on the 1 December 1918 boulevard\nFile:Bloc Turn Strada Victoriei din Suceava.jpg|Renovated apartment block on Victory street\nFile:Turnul_IFA2.jpg|IFA Tower, the city's tallest structure (with a total height surpassing 200 metres)\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Suceava}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Suceava}}\n* [http://www.primariasv.ro Suceava City Hall Official Site]\n* [https://suceava.media Suceava Media]\n* [https://suceava.photos Suceava Photos]\n* [https://suceava.travel Suceava Travel]\n* [https://suceava.website Suceava Website]\n\n{{Suceava County}}\n{{Cities in Romania}}\n{{RoJudCapitals}}{{Castles in Romania}}\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Capitals of Romanian counties]]\n[[Category:Place names of Hungarian origin in Romania]]\n[[Category:Castles in Romania]]\n[[Category:Former capitals of Romania]]\n[[Category:Bukovina]]\n[[Category:Duchy of Bukovina]]\n[[Category:Localities in Southern Bukovina]]\n[[Category:\u021ainutul Suceava]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Suceava County]]\n[[Category:Suceava| ]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Remove comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suceava"}
