tralian artists]]\n", "name_user": "HeyitsBen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAs featured artists:link relocation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/5_Seconds_of_Summer_discography"}
{"title_page": "Iso Grifo", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n| image =Iso grifo.jpg\n| name = Iso Grifo \n| production = 1963\u20131974\n|manufacturer=[[Iso Autoveicoli S.p.A.]]\n| engine = {{ubl | 5.4&nbsp;L ''[[Chevrolet small-block engine#327|Chevrolet 327]]'' [[OHV]] [[V8 engine|V8]] | 5.8&nbsp;L ''[[Ford 335 engine#351 Cleveland|Ford 351]]'' OHV V8 | 7.0&nbsp;L ''[[Chevrolet Big-Block engine#427|Chevrolet 427]]'' OHV V8 | 7.4&nbsp;L ''[[Chevrolet Big-Block engine#454|Chevrolet 454]]'' OHV V8 }}\n| transmission = 4-speed Muncie or 5-speed ZF manual transmission <br> 3-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]] (on request)\n| length = {{convert|174.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|69.7|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|47.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|layout=[[FR layout]]\n| body_style = 2-door [[coupe]]\n| weight = {{convert|3150|-|3550|lb|kg|abbr=on}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|98.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| designer = [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] at [[Gruppo Bertone|Bertone]]\n}}\n{{Listen\n |filename     =Iso Grifo A3C (1965).ogg\n |title        =1965 A3/C at Goodwood Festival of Speed 2010\n |type         =sound\n |style        =float:right\n}}\n\nThe '''Iso Grifo''' is a limited production [[grand tourer]] automobile manufactured by Italian [[Iso Autoveicoli S.p.A.]] between 1965 and 1974.<ref name=buckleyrees>Buckley; Rees. p155</ref> Intended to compete with [[Ferrari]] and [[Maserati]] GTs, it used a series of American [[power train]]s and components supplied by Chevrolet and Ford to ensure performance and maximize reliability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carligious.com/articles/forgotten-supercars/italian-passion-american-muscle-1965-1974-iso-grifo |title=Italian Passion, American Muscle: 1965 \u2013 1974 Iso Grifo |publisher=Carligious |date= |access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref><ref name=Gulett>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=ukst0yjvkDoC&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=iso+grifo+american&source=bl&ots=4qCnLsK2kW&sig=E6DOO21PLgn0OVWqAe9Wmqt9RuA&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiv18SykdXSAhUDDxoKHSoaA9AQ6AEIcjAN#v=onepage&q=iso%20grifo%20american&f=false |title=European Style with American Muscle - Mike Gulett - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.de |date= |accessdate=2017-06-22}}</ref><ref>https://www.classiccarchasers.com/single-post/2016/07/27/American-Muscle-Italian-Suit-1965-Iso-Grifo-A3C-Bizzarrini</ref> Styling was done by [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] at [[Gruppo Bertone|Bertone]], while the mechanicals were the work of [[Giotto Bizzarrini]].<ref name=scm201312>{{cite journal|last=Comer|first=Colin|title=1967 Iso Grifo GL 300|journal=[[Sports Car Market]]|date=December 2013|volume=25|issue=12|pages=54\u201355}}</ref>\n\nThe first production GL models appeared in 1965 and were powered by American [[Chevrolet small-block engine#327|Chevrolet Corvette small-block 327]] (5.4-litre) [[V8 engine|V8s]] fitted to American supplied [[Borg-Warner]] 4-speed manual transmissions. The 5.4-litre engine developed {{convert|300|hp|abbr=on}} in its standard form and could reach {{convert|110|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}} in first gear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoclassmagazine.com/web/iso-rivolta-a3c-b0207-that-special-heart/|title=Iso Rivolta A3/C #B0207 \u2013 That Special Heart|author=Manuel Bordini||publisher=Autoclass Magazine|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, the Grifo Series II appeared, with sleeker styling and hide-away headlights and powered by big-block Chevrolet [[Chevrolet Big-Block engine#454|454 V8]] (7.4-litre) engines. It was replaced in 1972 with the Grifo IR-8, which used a small-block [[Ford Boss 351 engine]] (5.8-litre) as its power train. This was the last new Iso of any type, as the manufacturer went bankrupt; it shut down and ceased all operations permanently in 1974.<ref name=buckleyrees/> The bankruptcy had a number of causes, perhaps the largest being the [[1973 oil crisis]], which significantly reduced demand for cars with large V8 engines.\n\n==Origin==\n[[File:Iso Grifo Rear.JPG|left|thumb|Iso Grifo Series I, rear view]]\n\nIso [[Joint-stock company|S.p.A.]] in [[Bresso]] was already well known for producing the high-performance [[Iso Rivolta IR 300]]; a sleek looking 2+2 Coupe based on a [[Chevrolet Corvette]] power and drive train.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://silodrome.com/short-film-iso-rivolta-chronicles/|title=The Iso Rivolta Chronicles Film Series|date=2017-06-06|website=Silodrome}}</ref> After leaving [[Ferrari]], in 1961 [[Giotto Bizzarrini]] set up ''\u201cPrototipi Bizzarrini\u201d'' in [[Livorno]], [[Tuscany]] where he designed and consulted for marques such as ATS, [[Lamborghini]], and Iso.<ref name=Fearnley>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/december-2003/90/bizza-express|title=Bizza express|magazine=[[Motor Sport Magazine]]|page=90|issue=December 2003|author=Paul Fearnley|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> In 1963, he designed the Iso Grifo A3/L (\"L\" for ''Lusso'', Italian for \"luxury\") for [[Renzo Rivolta]], who was looking for a follow-up to his IR 300.<ref name=Fearnley/> The body was designed by [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] at [[Gruppo Bertone|Bertone]], while Bizzarrini put his expertise in the mechanicals.<ref name=scm201312/>  \n\nBizzarrini figured there would also be a demand for a race version of the Grifo and developed the A3/C (C for Corsa) with a dramatic, modified alloy body.<ref name=Fearnley/> He later dubbed it his \u201cImproved GTO.\" He designed the [[Ferrari 250 GTO|250 GTO]] when he had worked for Ferrari. In the Corsa, he moved the engine back about {{Convert|40|mm|abbr=on}}, making the A3/C a front, mid-engined car. To adjust the timing, mechanics had to remove a piece of the dashboard.<ref name=Fearnley/> Both cars were being built simultaneously. When leaving the factory, both the [[Ferrari 250 GTO|250 GTO]] and Iso Grifo were originally fitted with [[Pirelli Cinturato]] 205VR15 tires (CN72).\n\nAt the [[Turin Motor Show]] that same year, Bertone showed the Grifo A3/L prototype while Iso showed off the unpainted competition version: the Iso Grifo A3/C.<ref name=Frankel>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/march-2016/84/power-without-glory|title=Power without glory|magazine=[[Motor Sport Magazine]]|page=84|issue=March 2016|author=Andrew Frankel|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> Both became successful in their own right, the road car receiving praise from the press, while the racer performed very well although it had been made on a much tighter budget compared to [[Ferrari]].<ref name=Frankel/> Rivolta also showed a prototype A3/L Spyder at the Geneva Motor Show.\n\n==Grifo GL &ndash; Bizzarrini A3/C split==\nIso concentrated on getting the A3/L ready for production, concentrating on some of the design changes that had to be made to the prototype. The car got a light face-lift that made it less aggressive in appearance. It was given a modified but reliable [[Chevrolet small-block engine#327|Chevrolet small-block 327]] Corvette engine [[V8 engine|V8]] (5.4 L) engine\u2014either in 300 or 350&nbsp;hp\u2014coupled to a [[Borg-Warner]] 4-speed top-loader. The engines were completely ordered and manufactured in the [[United States]]; they were shipped to Italy where they were taken apart and blueprinted before they were eventually installed in the cars. This was similar to the manufacture of the IR 300. With over {{convert|350|hp|abbr=on}} and a weight of less than {{convert|2200|lb|abbr=on}}, the vehicle was able to reach speeds over {{convert|275|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nIn 1964, the prototype A3/C raced at [[24 Hours of Le Mans|Le Mans]] (Edgar Berney/Pierre Noblet were drivers), running well until brake problems required a two-hour [[pit stop]].<ref name=Frankel/> The car resumed the race, finally finishing 14th. In 1965, the car performed better, finishing 9th at Le Mans.<ref name=Frankel/>\n\nThe production of the Iso Grifo GL started in 1965, but the Bizzarrini and Rivolta partnership quickly fell apart over the use of the name Grifo. This resulted in separate production of the Grifo GL and the competition Bizzarrini A3/C.<ref name=Frankel/><ref name=LM>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/december-1995/60/captain-scarlet|title=Captain Scarlet|magazine=[[Motor Sport Magazine]]|page=60|issue=December 1995|author=L M|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> The Grifo GL was produced at Bresso, while the A3/C was produced at Piero Drogo\u2019s Sports Cars of [[Modena]], under Bizzarini's strict supervision. Bizzarrini refined his A3/C , eventually developing his line of [[Bizzarrini Strada|Bizzarrini 5300 Stradas]] and Corsas.<ref name=Frankel/><ref name=LM/> Only 22 examples of the Grifo A3/C were constructed before Rivolta and Bizzarrini split.\n\nIn October 1966, the first Grifo (car #97) with a [[Targa top|targa]] top was shown at the Turin Motor Show. This was one of only thirteen Series I Targas ever built; later, only four series II Targas were built.<ref name=Gulett/>\n\n==Updates==\n[[File:Iso grifo can am.jpg|thumb|Iso Grifo Can Am with the characteristic 7-litre engine \"penthouse\" on the hood and Grifo Series II hide-away headlights]]\nIn 1968 the Grifo 7 Litri was introduced, featuring a Chevrolet L71 big-block engine, a Tri-Power version of the [[Chevrolet Big-Block engine#427|427 engine]]. The massive power plant required several mechanical changes to the car in order to fit, i.e. strengthened chassis components as well as an enlarged engine compartment with reinforced mounts. A large hood scoop (dubbed \"Penthouse\" due to its size) was added to clear for the engine's deck height. It produced an officially advertised minimum of {{convert|435|hp|abbr=on}} at 5800 rpm, which was a somewhat conservative rating given the engine's well-known and proven performance potential. The factory claimed it could reach a top speed of {{convert|300|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nIn 1970, a styling change was made to the nose section of the car for the Grifo Series II. It was given a sleeker look and hide-away headlights. In the IR-9 \"Can Am\" version, the engine was switched from the 427 engines to the newer, even more powerful Chevrolet 454 7.4 litre engine.\n\nIn 1972, the Grifo IR-8 was released, using a small-block Ford Boss 351 engines. These models can be recognized by their taller hood scoop. This was the final version of any Iso automobile, as Iso S.P.A. closed its doors in 1974 during the 1970s oil crisis.<ref name=buckleyrees/>\n\n==Totals==\nIn total, 322 Series I and 78 Series II cars were built for a total of 413 Grifos, 90 of which were 7-litre. The rarest are the Series II 5-speeds (23 units) and the Series II Targa (4 units). Due to their rarity today Grifos are desirable collectibles. A former employee of Iso, Roberto Negri, runs a small company in [[Clusone]], Italy, specializing in maintaining and restoring Grifos. There is a global community of Iso Grifo owners around the world, and they have gatherings a number of times each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isomillennium.it/index_news_ING.htm|title=Iso Website|website=Iso Website}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bizzarrini Strada]]\n* [[Ferrari 250 GTO]]\n* [[Ferrari Daytona]]\n* [[Lamborghini Miura]]\n* [[Maserati Ghibli]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Automobil Revue, catalog numbers 1963 through 1974\n* Winston Goodfellow: ''Iso Rivolta, The Man, The Machines''. Motorbooks International 2001. {{ISBN|88-7911-268-6}}.\n* {{Cite book|title=The World Encyclopedia of Cars|first1=Martin |last1=Buckley |first2=Chris |last2=Rees |publisher=Hermes House |year=1998 |pages=154\u2013155 |isbn=978-1-84038-083-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Iso Grifo}}\n* http://www.isorestorations.com/\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9578VD0R1bU The Red Grifo - Iso Grifo documentary short film]\n\n[[Category:Iso vehicles|G]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:1970s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1963]]\n[[Category:Grand tourers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| image =Iso grifo.jpg\n| name = Iso Grifo \n| production = 1963\u20131974\n|manufacturer=[[Iso Autoveicoli S.p.A.]]\n| engine = {{ubl | 5.4&nbsp;L ''[[Chevrolet small-block engine#327|Chevrolet 327]]'' [[OHV]] [[V8 engine|V8]] | 5.8&nbsp;L ''[[Ford 335 engine#351 Cleveland|Ford 351]]'' OHV V8 | 7.0&nbsp;L ''[[Chevrolet Big-Block engine#427|Chevrolet 427]]'' OHV V8 | 7.4&nbsp;L ''[[Chevrolet Big-Block engine#454|Chevrolet 454]]'' OHV V8 }}\n| transmission = 4-speed Muncie or 5-speed ZF manual transmission <br> 3-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]] (on request)\n| length = {{convert|174.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|69.7|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|47.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|layout=[[FR layout]]\n| body_style = 2-door [[coupe]]\n| weight = {{convert|3150|-|3550|lb|kg|abbr=on}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|98.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| designer = [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] at [[Gruppo Bertone|Bertone]]\n}}\n{{Listen\n |filename     =Iso Grifo A3C (1965).ogg\n |title        =1965 A3/C at Goodwood Festival of Speed 2010\n |type         =sound\n |style        =float:right\n}}\n\nThe '''Iso Grifo''' is a limited production [[grand tourer]] automobile manufactured by Italian [[Iso Autoveicoli S.p.A.]] between 1965 and 1974.<ref name=buckleyrees>Buckley; Rees. p155</ref> Intended to compete with [[Ferrari]] and [[Maserati]] GTs, it used a series of American [[power train]]s and components supplied by Chevrolet and Ford to ensure performance and maximize reliability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carligious.com/articles/forgotten-supercars/italian-passion-american-muscle-1965-1974-iso-grifo |title=Italian Passion, American Muscle: 1965 \u2013 1974 Iso Grifo |publisher=Carligious |date= |access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref><ref name=Gulett>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=ukst0yjvkDoC&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=iso+grifo+american&source=bl&ots=4qCnLsK2kW&sig=E6DOO21PLgn0OVWqAe9Wmqt9RuA&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiv18SykdXSAhUDDxoKHSoaA9AQ6AEIcjAN#v=onepage&q=iso%20grifo%20american&f=false |title=European Style with American Muscle - Mike Gulett - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.de |date= |accessdate=2017-06-22}}</ref><ref>https://www.classiccarchasers.com/single-post/2016/07/27/American-Muscle-Italian-Suit-1965-Iso-Grifo-A3C-Bizzarrini</ref> Styling was done by [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] at [[Gruppo Bertone|Bertone]], while the mechanicals were the work of [[Giotto Bizzarrini]].<ref name=scm201312>{{cite journal|last=Comer|first=Colin|title=1967 Iso Grifo GL 300|journal=[[Sports Car Market]]|date=December 2013|volume=25|issue=12|pages=54\u201355}}</ref>\n\nThe first production GL models appeared in 1965 and were powered by American [[Chevrolet small-block engine#327|Chevrolet Corvette small-block 327]] (5.4-litre) [[V8 engine|V8s]] fitted to American supplied [[Borg-Warner]] 4-speed manual transmissions. The 5.4-litre engine developed {{convert|300|hp|abbr=on}} in its standard form and could reach {{convert|110|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}} in first gear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoclassmagazine.com/web/iso-rivolta-a3c-b0207-that-special-heart/|title=Iso Rivolta A3/C #B0207 \u2013 That Special Heart|author=Manuel Bordini||publisher=Autoclass Magazine|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, the Grifo Series II appeared, with sleeker styling and hide-away headlights and powered by big-block Chevrolet [[Chevrolet Big-Block engine#454|454 V8]] (7.4-litre) engines. It was replaced in 1972 with the Grifo IR-8, which used a small-block [[Ford Boss 351 engine]] (5.8-litre) as its power train. This was the last new Iso of any type, as the manufacturer went bankrupt; it shut down and ceased all operations permanently in 1974.<ref name=buckleyrees/> The bankruptcy had a number of causes, perhaps the largest being the [[1973 oil crisis]], which significantly reduced demand for cars with large V8 engines.\n\n==Origin==\n[[File:Iso Grifo Rear.JPG|left|thumb|Iso Grifo Series I, rear view]]\n\nIso [[Joint-stock company|S.p.A.]] in [[Bresso]] was already well known for producing the high-performance [[Iso Rivolta IR 300]]; a sleek looking 2+2 Coupe based on a [[Chevrolet Corvette]] power and drive train.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://silodrome.com/short-film-iso-rivolta-chronicles/|title=The Iso Rivolta Chronicles Film Series|date=2017-06-06|website=Silodrome}}</ref> After leaving [[Ferrari]], in 1961 [[Giotto Bizzarrini]] set up ''\u201cPrototipi Bizzarrini\u201d'' in [[Livorno]], [[Tuscany]] where he designed and consulted for marques such as ATS, [[Lamborghini]], and Iso.<ref name=Fearnley>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/december-2003/90/bizza-express|title=Bizza express|magazine=[[Motor Sport Magazine]]|page=90|issue=December 2003|author=Paul Fearnley|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> In 1963, he designed the Iso Grifo A3/L (\"L\" for ''Lusso'', Italian for \"luxury\") for [[Renzo Rivolta]], who was looking for a follow-up to his IR 300.<ref name=Fearnley/> The body was designed by [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] at [[Gruppo Bertone|Bertone]], while Bizzarrini put his expertise in the mechanicals.<ref name=scm201312/>  \n\nBizzarrini figured there would also be a demand for a race version of the Grifo and developed the A3/C (C for Corsa) with a dramatic, modified alloy body.<ref name=Fearnley/> He later dubbed it his \u201cImproved GTO.\" He designed the [[Ferrari 250 GTO|250 GTO]] when he had worked for Ferrari. In the Corsa, he moved the engine back about {{Convert|40|mm|abbr=on}}, making the A3/C a front, mid-engined car. To adjust the timing, mechanics had to remove a piece of the dashboard.<ref name=Fearnley/> Both cars were being built simultaneously. When leaving the factory, both the [[Ferrari 250 GTO|250 GTO]] and Iso Grifo were originally fitted with [[Pirelli Cinturato]] 205VR15 tires (CN72).\n\nAt the [[Turin Motor Show]] that same year, Bertone showed the Grifo A3/L prototype while Iso showed off the unpainted competition version: the Iso Grifo A3/C.<ref name=Frankel>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/march-2016/84/power-without-glory|title=Power without glory|magazine=[[Motor Sport Magazine]]|page=84|issue=March 2016|author=Andrew Frankel|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> Both became successful in their own right, the road car receiving praise from the press, while the racer performed very well although it had been made on a much tighter budget compared to [[Ferrari]].<ref name=Frankel/> Rivolta also showed a prototype A3/L Spyder at the Geneva Motor Show.\n\n==Grifo GL &ndash; Bizzarrini A3/C split==\nIso concentrated on getting the A3/L ready for production, concentrating on some of the design changes that had to be made to the prototype. The car got a light face-lift that made it less aggressive in appearance. It was given a modified but reliable [[Chevrolet small-block engine#327|Chevrolet small-block 327]] Corvette engine [[V8 engine|V8]] (5.4 L) engine\u2014either in 300 or 350&nbsp;hp\u2014coupled to a [[Borg-Warner]] 4-speed top-loader. The engines were completely ordered and manufactured in the [[United States]]; they were shipped to Italy where they were taken apart and blueprinted before they were eventually installed in the cars. This was similar to the manufacture of the IR 300. With over {{convert|350|hp|abbr=on}} and a weight of less than {{convert|2200|lb|abbr=on}}, the vehicle was able to reach speeds over {{convert|275|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nIn 1964, the prototype A3/C raced at [[24 Hours of Le Mans|Le Mans]] (Edgar Berney/Pierre Noblet were drivers), running well until brake problems required a two-hour [[pit stop]].<ref name=Frankel/> The car resumed the race, finally finishing 14th. In 1965, the car performed better, finishing 9th at Le Mans.<ref name=Frankel/>\n\nThe production of the Iso Grifo GL started in 1965, but the Bizzarrini and Rivolta partnership quickly fell apart over the use of the name Grifo. This resulted in separate production of the Grifo GL and the competition Bizzarrini A3/C.<ref name=Frankel/><ref name=LM>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/december-1995/60/captain-scarlet|title=Captain Scarlet|magazine=[[Motor Sport Magazine]]|page=60|issue=December 1995|author=L M|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> The Grifo GL was produced at Bresso, while the A3/C was produced at Piero Drogo\u2019s Sports Cars of [[Modena]], under Bizzarini's strict supervision. Bizzarrini refined his A3/C , eventually developing his line of [[Bizzarrini Strada|Bizzarrini 5300 Stradas]] and Corsas.<ref name=Frankel/><ref name=LM/> Only 22 examples of the Grifo A3/C were constructed before Rivolta and Bizzarrini split.\n\nIn October 1966, the first Grifo (car #97) with a [[targa]] top was shown at the Turin Motor Show. This was one of only thirteen Series I Targas ever built; later, only four series II Targas were built.<ref name=Gulett/>\n\n==Updates==\n[[File:Iso grifo can am.jpg|thumb|Iso Grifo Can Am with the characteristic 7-litre engine \"penthouse\" on the hood and Grifo Series II hide-away headlights]]\nIn 1968 the Grifo 7 Litri was introduced, featuring a Chevrolet L71 big-block engine, a Tri-Power version of the [[Chevrolet Big-Block engine#427|427 engine]]. The massive power plant required several mechanical changes to the car in order to fit, i.e. strengthened chassis components as well as an enlarged engine compartment with reinforced mounts. A large hood scoop (dubbed \"Penthouse\" due to its size) was added to clear for the engine's deck height. It produced an officially advertised minimum of {{convert|435|hp|abbr=on}} at 5800 rpm, which was a somewhat conservative rating given the engine's well-known and proven performance potential. The factory claimed it could reach a top speed of {{convert|300|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nIn 1970, a styling change was made to the nose section of the car for the Grifo Series II. It was given a sleeker look and hide-away headlights. In the IR-9 \"Can Am\" version, the engine was switched from the 427 engines to the newer, even more powerful Chevrolet 454 7.4 litre engine.\n\nIn 1972, the Grifo IR-8 was released, using a small-block Ford Boss 351 engines. These models can be recognized by their taller hood scoop. This was the final version of any Iso automobile, as Iso S.P.A. closed its doors in 1974 during the 1970s oil crisis.<ref name=buckleyrees/>\n\n==Totals==\nIn total, 322 Series I and 78 Series II cars were built for a total of 413 Grifos, 90 of which were 7-litre. The rarest are the Series II 5-speeds (23 units) and the Series II Targa (4 units). Due to their rarity today Grifos are desirable collectibles. A former employee of Iso, Roberto Negri, runs a small company in [[Clusone]], Italy, specializing in maintaining and restoring Grifos. There is a global community of Iso Grifo owners around the world, and they have gatherings a number of times each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isomillennium.it/index_news_ING.htm|title=Iso Website|website=Iso Website}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bizzarrini Strada]]\n* [[Ferrari 250 GTO]]\n* [[Ferrari Daytona]]\n* [[Lamborghini Miura]]\n* [[Maserati Ghibli]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Automobil Revue, catalog numbers 1963 through 1974\n* Winston Goodfellow: ''Iso Rivolta, The Man, The Machines''. Motorbooks International 2001. {{ISBN|88-7911-268-6}}.\n* {{Cite book|title=The World Encyclopedia of Cars|first1=Martin |last1=Buckley |first2=Chris |last2=Rees |publisher=Hermes House |year=1998 |pages=154\u2013155 |isbn=978-1-84038-083-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Iso Grifo}}\n* http://www.isorestorations.com/\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9578VD0R1bU The Red Grifo - Iso Grifo documentary short film]\n\n[[Category:Iso vehicles|G]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:1970s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1963]]\n[[Category:Grand tourers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toTarga(link changed toTarga top) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iso_Grifo"}
{"title_page": "Leapfrogging (strategy)", "text_new": "{{about|war tactics|the biological migration movement|Island hopping|the tactical counterpart|Leapfrogging (infantry)}}\n\n[[File:Second world war asia 1943-1945 map de.png|thumb|300px|right|Allied island-hopping campaign 1943\u20131945:<br>\n  Blue \u2013 Japanese-held territory Aug. 1945<br>\n  Dark red \u2013 Allied territory<br>\n  Red \u2013 Occupied Nov. 1943<br>\n  Dark pink \u2013 Occupied Apr. 1944<br>\n  Pink \u2013 Occupied Oct. 1944<br>\n  Light pink \u2013 Occupied Aug. 1945]]\n'''Leapfrogging''', also known as '''island hopping''', was a [[military strategy]] employed by the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] in the [[Pacific War]] against the [[Empire of Japan]] and the [[Axis powers]] during [[World War II]].{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}{{dubious|date=September 2019}}\n\n== Background ==\nfirst I have to make this clear breyden cicklinski reeks of cat pee and needs to take a shower but besides that By the late 17th century, the U.S. had several interests in the western Pacific to defend; namely, access to the Chinese market, and its colonies \u2013 the [[Commonwealth of the Philippines|Philippines]] and [[Guam]] \u2013 which the U.S. had gained as a result of the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] (1898).  After Japan's victories in the [[First Sino-Japanese War|Sino-Japanese War]] (1894\u201395) and in the [[Russo-Japanese War]] of 1904, the U.S. began to regard Japan as a potential threat to its interests in the western Pacific.{{Sfn | Asada | 2006 | pp = 11, 18}}  This antagonism was intensified by Japan's objections to an attempt to [[Overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii|annex Hawaii]] to the U.S. (1893)<ref>On this occasion, Japan sent the cruiser. The cruiser was a very tactical ship used to attck the U.S in attle. island-hopping helped the US defeat Japan.\n to Honolulu, Hawaii; the ''Naniwa'' arrived at Hawaii on February 23, 1894.  See:  William L. Neumann, \"The First Abrasions\" in: Ellis S. Krauss and Benjamin Nyblade, ed.s, ''Japan and North America: First contacts to the Pacific War'', Volume 1, (London, England: RouteledgeCurzon, 2004), [https://books.google.com/books?id=io6auqu0n9IC&pg=PA114#v=onepage&q&f=false page 114].</ref> and by Japan's objections to discrimination against Japanese immigrants both in Hawaii (1897) \u2013 on this occasion, Japan sent the cruiser [[Japanese cruiser Naniwa|''Naniwa'']] to [[Honolulu]], Hawaii{{Sfn | Asada | 2006 | p = 10}}<ref>See:\n*  [http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1897-05-04/ed-1/seq-1/ \"Japan's Points:  Hawaiian government to be asked questions.\"] (May 4, 1897) ''Hawaiian Gazette'', vol. 32, no 36, page 1.\n*  [http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1897-05-07/ed-1/seq-1/ \"No Arbitration:  Minister Shimamura on indemnity claim.\"] (May 7, 1897), ''Hawaiian Gazette'', vol. 32, no. 37, page 1.</ref> \u2013 and in California (1906, 1913).{{Sfn | Asada | 2006 |pp = 10, 11, 18, 20}}  As a result, the U.S. Navy began to draft, as early as 1897, war plans against Japan, which were eventually code-named \"[[War Plan Orange]]\".  The war plan of 1911, which was drafted under Rear Admiral [[Raymond P. Rodgers]], included an island-hopping strategy for approaching Japan.{{Sfn | Asada | 2006 | pp = 12\u201313, 22}}\n\nAfter World War I, the [[Treaty of Versailles|Versailles Treaty]] gave Japan a mandate over former German colonies in the western Pacific; specifically, the [[Mariana Islands|Mariana]], [[Marshall Islands|Marshall]], and [[Caroline Islands|Caroline]] Islands.  If these islands were fortified, Japan could, in principle, deny the U.S. access to its interests in the western Pacific.  Therefore, in 1921, Major [[Earl Hancock Ellis]] of the [[United States Marine Corps|U.S. Marine Corps]] drafted \"Plan 712, Advanced Base Operations in Micronesia,\" a plan for war against Japan which updated War Plan Orange by incorporating modern military technology (submarines, aircraft, etc.) and which again included an island-hopping strategy.<ref>See:\n*  {{Citation | title = Plan 712, Advanced Base Operations in Micronesia | url = http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USMC/ref/AdvBaseOps/ | publisher = iBiblio }}\n*  {{Citation | title = Advanced Base Operations in Micronesia | url = https://www.mca-marines.org/sites/default/files/OperationPlan712H.pdf | publisher = Marine Corps Association and Foundation | access-date = 2017-12-18 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160805081229/https://www.mca-marines.org/sites/default/files/OperationPlan712H.pdf | archive-date = 2016-08-05 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Shortly afterwards, a British reporter on naval affairs, [[Hector Charles Bywater]], publicized the prospect of a Japanese-American war in his books ''Seapower in the Pacific'' (1921)<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bywater|first1=Hector C.|title=Sea-power in the Pacific: A Study of the American-Japanese Naval Problem|date=1921|publisher=Constable and Co., Ltd.|location=London, England|url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924023233822#page/n7/mode/2up}}</ref> and ''[[The Great Pacific War]]'' (1925), which detailed an island-hopping str\n The books were read not only by Americans but by senior officers of the [[Japanese Imperial Navy]],<ref name=\"honan197012\">{{cite journal | url = http://www.americanheritage.com/content/japan-strikes-1941 | title = Japan Strikes: 1941 | last =Honan | first = William H |author-link=William H. Honan | journal=American Heritage |date=Dec 1970 | volume=22 | issue=1 | pages=12\u201315, 91\u201395}}</ref> who used \"island-hopping\" in their successful [[Pacific War#Japanese offensives, 1941\u201342|southeast Asia offensives in 1941 and 1942]].<ref name=\"life1942062932\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KlAEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA1&pg=PA32#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=War in Aleutians | work=Life | date=1942-06-29 | accessdate =November 17, 2011 | pages=32}}</ref>\n\n== Rationale and use ==\nThis strategy was possible in part because the Allies used [[submarine]] and air attacks to [[blockade]] and isolate Japanese bases, weakening their garrisons and reducing the Japanese ability to resupply and reinforce them. Thus troops on islands which had been bypassed, such as the major base at [[Rabaul]], were useless to the Japanese war effort and left to \"wither on the vine\".  [[General Douglas MacArthur]] greatly supported this strategy in his effort to regain the [[Philippines]] from [[Japanese occupation of the Philippines|Japanese occupation]].  This strategy began to be implemented in late 1943 in [[Operation Cartwheel]].{{Sfn | Roehrs | Renzi | 2004 | p = 122}}  While MacArthur claimed to have invented the strategy, it initially came out of the Navy.{{Sfn | Roehrs | Renzi | 2004 | p = 122}}\n\n== Advantages ==\nLeapfrogging would allow the United States forces to reach Japan quickly and not expend the time, manpower, and supplies to capture every Japanese-held island on the way. It would give the Allies the advantage of surprise and keep the Japanese off balance.{{Sfn | Roehrs | Renzi | 2004 | p = 119}}  The overall leapfrogging strategy would involve two prongs. A force led by [[Admiral Chester Nimitz]], with a smaller land force and larger fleet, would advance north towards the island and capture the [[Gilbert Islands|Gilbert]] and [[Marshall Islands]] and the [[Marianas]], going generally in the direction of the [[Bonin Islands]].{{Sfn | Collier | 1967 | p = 480}}  The southern prong, led by [[Douglas MacArthur|General MacArthur]] and with larger land forces, would take the [[Solomon Islands|Solomons]], [[New Guinea]], the [[Bismarck Archipelago]], advancing toward the Philippines.{{Sfn | Collier | 1967 | p = 480}}\n\n== Exceptions ==\nThe principle of leapfrogging was not always followed in the Pacific. When MacArthur moved south to attack [[Mindanao]] after capturing the northern [[Philippines]], and when he instigated the reconquest of portions of [[Borneo]], he violated the \"basic tenets\" of island hopping.{{Sfn | Roehrs | Renzi | 2004 | p = 151}}  In the first case, this may have been motivated by MacArthur's promise to return to the people of the Philippines as soon as possible.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Seabee]]\n* [[Unsinkable aircraft carrier]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{citation | first = Sadao | last = Asada | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=B2FYVG-mBn0C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false | title = From Mahan to Pearl Harbor: The Imperial Japanese Navy and the United States | location = Annapolis, Maryland, USA | publisher = Naval Institute Press | year= 2006| isbn = 9781557500427 }}.\n* {{Citation | last = Collier | first = Basil | title = The Second World War: a Military History | place = New York | publisher = William Morrow & Co | year = 1967}}.\n* {{Citation | last1 = Roehrs | first1 = Mark D | first2 = William A | last2 = Renzi | title = World War II in the Pacific | edition = 2nd | place = London | publisher = ME Sharpe | year = 2004}}.\n\n{{World War II}}\n\n[[Category:Military strategy]]\n[[Category:Pacific theatre of World War II]]\n[[Category:Military logistics]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|war tactics|the biological migration movement|Island hopping|the tactical counterpart|Leapfrogging (infantry)}}\n\n[[File:Second world war asia 1943-1945 map de.png|thumb|300px|right|Allied island-hopping campaign 1943\u20131945:<br>\n  Blue \u2013 Japanese-held territory Aug. 1945<br>\n  Dark red \u2013 Allied territory<br>\n  Red \u2013 Occupied Nov. 1943<br>\n  Dark pink \u2013 Occupied Apr. 1944<br>\n  Pink \u2013 Occupied Oct. 1944<br>\n  Light pink \u2013 Occupied Aug. 1945]]\n'''Leapfrogging''', also known as '''island hopping''', was a [[military strategy]] employed by the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] in the [[Pacific War]] against the [[Empire of Japan]] and the [[Axis powers]] during [[World War II]].{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}{{dubious|date=September 2019}}\n\n== Background ==\nBy the late 19th century, the U.S. had several interests in the western Pacific to defend; namely, access to the Chinese market, and its colonies \u2013 the [[Commonwealth of the Philippines|Philippines]] and [[Guam]] \u2013 which the U.S. had gained as a result of the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] (1898).  After Japan's victories in the [[First Sino-Japanese War|Sino-Japanese War]] (1894\u201395) and in the [[Russo-Japanese War]] of 1904, the U.S. began to regard Japan as a potential threat to its interests in the western Pacific.{{Sfn | Asada | 2006 | pp = 11, 18}}  This antagonism was intensified by Japan's objections to an attempt to [[Overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii|annex Hawaii]] to the U.S. (1893)<ref>On this occasion, Japan sent the cruiser. The cruiser was a very tactical ship used to attck the U.S in attle. island-hopping helped the US defeat Japan.\n to Honolulu, Hawaii; the ''Naniwa'' arrived at Hawaii on February 23, 1894.  See:  William L. Neumann, \"The First Abrasions\" in: Ellis S. Krauss and Benjamin Nyblade, ed.s, ''Japan and North America: First contacts to the Pacific War'', Volume 1, (London, England: RouteledgeCurzon, 2004), [https://books.google.com/books?id=io6auqu0n9IC&pg=PA114#v=onepage&q&f=false page 114].</ref> and by Japan's objections to discrimination against Japanese immigrants both in Hawaii (1897) \u2013 on this occasion, Japan sent the cruiser [[Japanese cruiser Naniwa|''Naniwa'']] to [[Honolulu]], Hawaii{{Sfn | Asada | 2006 | p = 10}}<ref>See:\n*  [http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1897-05-04/ed-1/seq-1/ \"Japan's Points:  Hawaiian government to be asked questions.\"] (May 4, 1897) ''Hawaiian Gazette'', vol. 32, no 36, page 1.\n*  [http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1897-05-07/ed-1/seq-1/ \"No Arbitration:  Minister Shimamura on indemnity claim.\"] (May 7, 1897), ''Hawaiian Gazette'', vol. 32, no. 37, page 1.</ref> \u2013 and in California (1906, 1913).{{Sfn | Asada | 2006 |pp = 10, 11, 18, 20}}  As a result, the U.S. Navy began to draft, as early as 1897, war plans against Japan, which were eventually code-named \"[[War Plan Orange]]\".  The war plan of 1911, which was drafted under Rear Admiral [[Raymond P. Rodgers]], included an island-hopping strategy for approaching Japan.{{Sfn | Asada | 2006 | pp = 12\u201313, 22}}\n\nAfter World War I, the [[Treaty of Versailles|Versailles Treaty]] gave Japan a mandate over former German colonies in the western Pacific; specifically, the [[Mariana Islands|Mariana]], [[Marshall Islands|Marshall]], and [[Caroline Islands|Caroline]] Islands.  If these islands were fortified, Japan could, in principle, deny the U.S. access to its interests in the western Pacific.  Therefore, in 1921, Major [[Earl Hancock Ellis]] of the [[United States Marine Corps|U.S. Marine Corps]] drafted \"Plan 712, Advanced Base Operations in Micronesia,\" a plan for war against Japan which updated War Plan Orange by incorporating modern military technology (submarines, aircraft, etc.) and which again included an island-hopping strategy.<ref>See:\n*  {{Citation | title = Plan 712, Advanced Base Operations in Micronesia | url = http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USMC/ref/AdvBaseOps/ | publisher = iBiblio }}\n*  {{Citation | title = Advanced Base Operations in Micronesia | url = https://www.mca-marines.org/sites/default/files/OperationPlan712H.pdf | publisher = Marine Corps Association and Foundation | access-date = 2017-12-18 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160805081229/https://www.mca-marines.org/sites/default/files/OperationPlan712H.pdf | archive-date = 2016-08-05 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Shortly afterwards, a British reporter on naval affairs, [[Hector Charles Bywater]], publicized the prospect of a Japanese-American war in his books ''Seapower in the Pacific'' (1921)<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bywater|first1=Hector C.|title=Sea-power in the Pacific: A Study of the American-Japanese Naval Problem|date=1921|publisher=Constable and Co., Ltd.|location=London, England|url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924023233822#page/n7/mode/2up}}</ref> and ''[[The Great Pacific War]]'' (1925), which detailed an island-hopping str\n The books were read not only by Americans but by senior officers of the [[Japanese Imperial Navy]],<ref name=\"honan197012\">{{cite journal | url = http://www.americanheritage.com/content/japan-strikes-1941 | title = Japan Strikes: 1941 | last =Honan | first = William H |author-link=William H. Honan | journal=American Heritage |date=Dec 1970 | volume=22 | issue=1 | pages=12\u201315, 91\u201395}}</ref> who used \"island-hopping\" in their successful [[Pacific War#Japanese offensives, 1941\u201342|southeast Asia offensives in 1941 and 1942]].<ref name=\"life1942062932\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KlAEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA1&pg=PA32#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=War in Aleutians | work=Life | date=1942-06-29 | accessdate =November 17, 2011 | pages=32}}</ref>\n\n== Rationale and use ==\nThis strategy was possible in part because the Allies used [[submarine]] and air attacks to [[blockade]] and isolate Japanese bases, weakening their garrisons and reducing the Japanese ability to resupply and reinforce them. Thus troops on islands which had been bypassed, such as the major base at [[Rabaul]], were useless to the Japanese war effort and left to \"wither on the vine\".  [[General Douglas MacArthur]] greatly supported this strategy in his effort to regain the [[Philippines]] from [[Japanese occupation of the Philippines|Japanese occupation]].  This strategy began to be implemented in late 1943 in [[Operation Cartwheel]].{{Sfn | Roehrs | Renzi | 2004 | p = 122}}  While MacArthur claimed to have invented the strategy, it initially came out of the Navy.{{Sfn | Roehrs | Renzi | 2004 | p = 122}}\n\n== Advantages ==\nLeapfrogging would allow the United States forces to reach Japan quickly and not expend the time, manpower, and supplies to capture every Japanese-held island on the way. It would give the Allies the advantage of surprise and keep the Japanese off balance.{{Sfn | Roehrs | Renzi | 2004 | p = 119}}  The overall leapfrogging strategy would involve two prongs. A force led by [[Admiral Chester Nimitz]], with a smaller land force and larger fleet, would advance north towards the island and capture the [[Gilbert Islands|Gilbert]] and [[Marshall Islands]] and the [[Marianas]], going generally in the direction of the [[Bonin Islands]].{{Sfn | Collier | 1967 | p = 480}}  The southern prong, led by [[Douglas MacArthur|General MacArthur]] and with larger land forces, would take the [[Solomon Islands|Solomons]], [[New Guinea]], the [[Bismarck Archipelago]], advancing toward the Philippines.{{Sfn | Collier | 1967 | p = 480}}\n\n== Exceptions ==\nThe principle of leapfrogging was not always followed in the Pacific. When MacArthur moved south to attack [[Mindanao]] after capturing the northern [[Philippines]], and when he instigated the reconquest of portions of [[Borneo]], he violated the \"basic tenets\" of island hopping.{{Sfn | Roehrs | Renzi | 2004 | p = 151}}  In the first case, this may have been motivated by MacArthur's promise to return to the people of the Philippines as soon as possible.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Seabee]]\n* [[Unsinkable aircraft carrier]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{citation | first = Sadao | last = Asada | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=B2FYVG-mBn0C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false | title = From Mahan to Pearl Harbor: The Imperial Japanese Navy and the United States | location = Annapolis, Maryland, USA | publisher = Naval Institute Press | year= 2006| isbn = 9781557500427 }}.\n* {{Citation | last = Collier | first = Basil | title = The Second World War: a Military History | place = New York | publisher = William Morrow & Co | year = 1967}}.\n* {{Citation | last1 =