{"title_page": "Ellie Goulding discography", "text_new": "{{short description|Ellie Goulding discography}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist       = [[Ellie Goulding]]\n| Image        = POS17 @Kristsll-503 (36005608765).jpg\n| Caption      = Goulding performing in July 2017\n| Studio       = 3\n| Music videos = 35\n| EP           = 7\n| Singles      = 35\n| Option       = 2\n| Option name  = Reissues\n| 1Option      = 1\n| 1Option name = Remix albums\n| 2Option      = 5\n| 2Option name = Promotional singles\n}}\nEnglish singer and songwriter [[Ellie Goulding]] has released three [[studio album]]s, one [[remix album]], seven [[extended play]]s, 35 [[Single (music)|singles]] (including eight as a featured artist), five [[promotional single]]s and 35 [[music video]]s. As of March 2020, Goulding had sold 15 million albums and 102 million singles worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressparty.com/pg/newsdesk/umusic/view/206495/ |title=Ellie Goulding Releases New Single \"Worry About Me\" Featuring Blackbear|work=Pressparty|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> Additionally, she had sold over 1.5 million albums and over 4.3 million singles (including collaborations) in the United Kingdom alone as of February 2014.<ref name=\"Feb2014sales\">{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Alan |url=https://www.musicweek.com/analysis/read/official-charts-analysis-clean-bandit-single-sells-another-137k/057506 |title=Official Charts Analysis: Clean Bandit single sells another 137k |work=[[Music Week]] |date=3 February 2014 |accessdate=24 November 2018 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAfter signing to [[Polydor Records]] in July 2009,<ref>{{cite web |last=Ferguson |first=Paul |url=http://www.herefordtimes.com/news/4581912.Herefordshire_singer__Ellie_Goulding__signs_recording_deal_with_Polydor/ |title=Herefordshire singer, Ellie Goulding, signs recording deal with Polydor |work=[[Hereford Times]] |date=4 September 2009 |accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref> Goulding released her debut extended play, ''[[An Introduction to Ellie Goulding]]'', in December of that year. It was followed by the release of her debut studio album, ''[[Lights (Ellie Goulding album)|Lights]]'', in February 2010. The album debuted at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and subsequently earned a double platinum certification from the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI).<ref name=\"UK\"/><ref name=\"BPI\"/> It spawned four singles: \"[[Under the Sheets]]\", \"[[Starry Eyed (Ellie Goulding song)|Starry Eyed]]\", \"[[Guns and Horses]]\" and \"[[The Writer (song)|The Writer]]\", which reached numbers 53, four, 26 and 19 on the [[UK Singles Chart]], respectively.<ref name=\"UK\"/> In November 2010, the album was re-released as ''Bright Lights''; it featured seven new songs, including a cover version of [[Elton John]]'s \"[[Your Song#Ellie Goulding version|Your Song]]\", which peaked at number two on the UK Singles Chart.<ref name=\"UK\"/> The sixth single to be lifted from the album, \"[[Lights (Ellie Goulding song)|Lights]]\", peaked at number 49 in the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"UK\"/> while becoming Goulding's highest-charting single to date in the United States and Canada, where it reached numbers two and seven, respectively.<ref name=\"US-singles\"/><ref name=\"CAN-singles\"/>\n\nGoulding's second studio album, ''[[Halcyon (album)|Halcyon]]'', was released in October 2012, peaking at number one in the UK and reaching the top 10 in Canada, Germany and the US.<ref name=\"UK\"/><ref name=\"CAN-albums\"/><ref name=\"GER\"/><ref name=\"US-albums\"/> It was later certified triple platinum by the BPI and gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref name=\"BPI\"/><ref name=\"RIAA\"/> The album's lead single, \"[[Anything Could Happen]]\", earned Goulding her third top-five song on the UK Singles Chart when it peaked at number five.<ref name=\"UK\"/> The track also became her first charting single in Australia (number 20) and second appearance on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] (number 47).<ref name=\"US-singles\"/><ref name=\"AUS\"/> Subsequent singles \"[[Figure 8 (song)|Figure 8]]\" and \"[[Explosions (song)|Explosions]]\" peaked at numbers 33 and 13 on the UK chart, respectively.<ref name=\"UK\"/> In 2013, Goulding was featured on [[Calvin Harris]]'s single \"[[I Need Your Love (Calvin Harris song)|I Need Your Love]]\", which reached number four in the UK.<ref name=\"UK\"/> That same year, her album ''Halcyon'' was reissued as ''[[Halcyon Days (Ellie Goulding album)|Halcyon Days]]'', containing 10 additional tracks. It was preceded by the lead single \"[[Burn (Ellie Goulding song)|Burn]]\", which gave Goulding her first UK number-one single.<ref name=\"UK\"/> The song also became an international success, charting inside the top 10 in several countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Ellie+Goulding&titel=Burn&cat=s |title=Ellie Goulding \u2013 Burn |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Ultratop]] |accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref> ''Halcyon Days'' yielded two more singles: a cover of \"[[How Long Will I Love You?#Ellie Goulding version|How Long Will I Love You]]\" by [[The Waterboys]] and \"[[Goodness Gracious (Ellie Goulding song)|Goodness Gracious]]\".\n\nIn 2014, Goulding recorded the song \"[[Beating Heart (Ellie Goulding song)|Beating Heart]]\" for the [[Divergent: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|soundtrack]] to ''[[Divergent (film)|Divergent]]'', and she also released her second collaboration with Calvin Harris, titled \"[[Outside (Calvin Harris song)|Outside]]\". The following year, she contributed the song \"[[Love Me like You Do]]\" to the [[Fifty Shades of Grey: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|soundtrack]] to ''[[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|Fifty Shades of Grey]]''. \"Love Me like You Do\" became a commercial success worldwide, earning Goulding her second UK number one and topping the charts in several other countries.<ref name=\"UK\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Ellie+Goulding&titel=Love+Me+Like+You+Do&cat=s |title=Ellie Goulding \u2013 Love Me Like You Do |language=Dutch |publisher=Ultratop |accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref> Goulding's third studio album, ''[[Delirium (Ellie Goulding album)|Delirium]]'', was released in November 2015 and peaked at number three in the United Kingdom, the United States and Australia,<ref name=\"UK\"/><ref name=\"US-albums\"/><ref name=\"AUS\"/> while reaching the top five in several other countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Ellie+Goulding&titel=Delirium&cat=a |title=Ellie Goulding \u2013 Delirium |language=Dutch |publisher=Ultratop |accessdate=13 August 2016}}</ref> The album spawned three singles: \"[[On My Mind (Ellie Goulding song)|On My Mind]]\", \"[[Army (Ellie Goulding song)|Army]]\" and \"[[Something in the Way You Move]]\".\n\n==Albums==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with selected chart positions, sales figures and certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:9em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:17em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Sales\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br><ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/5933/ellie-goulding/ |title=Ellie Goulding |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref name=\"AUS\">Peak chart positions for albums and singles in Australia:\n* All exc